Enclosing_Summary: Univallate hillfort with complete circuit, but the ditch is only visible on S and E sides, destroyed, or never built, elsewhere. The rampart reaches up to 4.5m high to S, where ditch to 1.5m, but only 0.5m in W.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Little surface evidence of features and the bank is possibly earthen. A berm exists to the N and W, created at the base of the rampart. Possible internal revetments were found within the ramparts.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Main ditch only present on the S and E sides, elsewhere destroyed or never constructed.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined differentially by single rampart to 5.1m high, with part-buried outer ditch and counterscarp bank to N, E and possibly S, rising to 1.8m. Counterscarp bank is complex and difficult to unravel and probably also existed on W. Mostly removed by cultivation and on E merges into a berm before re-appearing; possibly result of landslip or not finished.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts are irregular which makes assessment difficult, but generally complete the circuit.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Bank possibly earthen. Counterscarp bank complex and difficult to unravel and probably also existed on W. Mostly removed by cultivation, and on E merges into a berm before reappearing; possibly result of landslip or not finished.

Enclosing_Summary: Three ramparts and ditches on the N. Although damaged, inner and outer ramparts continuous on the W side, the outer altered and reduced. Also damaged because of an ancient landslide, the ramparts are discontinuous on the E and S.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts damaged and discontinuous. On the W the inner and outer ramparts are continuous, the latter altered and reduced.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches in evidence in the N, but absent or discontinuous elsewhere.

Enclosing_Summary: Steep natural scarp artificially scarped with berm to 7.5m at the NW. Possible slight inner rampart on the N; remaining sides with simple rampart minus ditch, possibly filled.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts are slight but complete the circuit.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank with a berm to 7.5m at the NW side.

Enclosing_Summary: In Phase I, c. 3ha were enclosed by a slight bank (in proportion) and impressive ditch above an artificially steepened scarp. Here the counterscarp is massive in places. In Phase II, the enclosure was enlarged to about 13.5ha following the 305m contour. The ramparts of the main Phase II enclosure are entirely visible.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site is very long and sinuous. Phased construction.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts of the Phase II overall enclosure, closely follow the 305m contour.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Surface evidence of an earthen bank and counterscarp bank.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: The excavations found that In Phase I, c. 3ha were enclosed by a slight bank (in proportion) and impressive ditch above an artificially steepened scarp. Here the counterscap is massive in places. In Phase II, the enclosure was enlarged to about 13.5ha following the 305m contour.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The Phase I ditch is the principal feature, the bank slight. In Phase II the ditch is deep (as much as 11.6m below rampart) and massive in places. The Shire Ditch is medieval.

Enclosing_Summary: Cropmark site. Three widely-spaced ditches appear to cut off the promontory with steep W slopes, less steep to the N and S. Possible earthworks may exist in woodland to the W, but no access to allowed to determine this. To the N a field boundary may indicate the site of rampart.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Cropmark only and its size or area has not been determined.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Because of the nature of the cropmark this is unclear, but possibly three.

Enclosing_Summary: Scarped natural slope on the direct W and N sides, with two ramparts and ditches on the weaker S. To the SW there are three ramparts and second ditch. The S side has substantial ramparts as opposed to the naturally defended N.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site makes full use of the natural contours.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Scarped natural slope on the direct W and N sides. Strong natural defence on the N and W where there is a sheer drop to river.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank. Track runs from the ditch in the NW corner at the base of the scarp edge and possibly masking/utilising a berm. Prominent counterscarp running from the SW corner to NW corner.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The N and W sides are naturally strong and defended by a ditch only. Ditches with ramparts elsewhere.

Enclosing_Summary: Defended on S by rampart rising to nearly 2m above ground surface. Elsewhere there is a scarped natural slope with berm and traces of outer bank on W side. Unusual western defences as located 40m downslope from the interior with a berm at the base of the scarp, then a ditch and counterscarp.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Major use of natural slopes define the site.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts form the circuit making full use of the natural slopes.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Scarped natural slopes with berm and counterscarp  a feature of the site.

Enclosing_Summary: Double scarp with wide berm, with traces of an outer rampart to the berm on all sides apart from most of the E where steep natural slopes form the defence.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Because of the steep slopes on the E,  the site assumes a D-shape form.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Natural defence to most of the E side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Wide berm evident with possible earthen bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No traces of ditch, but possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: The W enclosure is defended by three ramparts and two intermediate ditches on the N, and by a berm on the S with a steep natural slope below a steepened scarp above. This is divided from the E enclosure by a double rampart and medial ditch, itself having two ramparts with medial ditch, the outer rampart mostly gone. There is a spoil ditch within the inner rampart. The N and smallest enclosure has a double rampart and medial ditch, the outer fragmented. Complex detail to the defences of the three enclosures.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The first phase measured 3.2ha; the Phase II to 5.8ha. The three enclosures suggest a multi- period site, but there is no direct evidence for this. Multi period details not determined.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: A complex series of banks define the site. Multi period details not determined.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditches are very complex and vary between two and three.

Enclosing_Summary: Substantial ramparts and ditch, the inner rampart (to 9m) higher than the outer (to 4m), with medial ditch. The height of the S rampart is augmented by scarping the natural hillslope with a berm along the base of the scarp. The detail is lost in places and exact nature not determined.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: The wide bank noted as a possible rampart was shown by excavation to be a lynchet or headland of the medieval cultivation of the interior. Details of 2008 investigation awaited.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Medial ditches, their detail to be determined.

Enclosing_Summary: Three ramparts and deep ditches define the site. Main rampart c. 10m above the external ditch with two lesser outer banks, the most S suggested as incomplete.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Phased construction and seven periods of occupation suggested between 450 BC to AD 49 on the evidence of gateway renewal. Firstly a rampart (later removed) and ditch (still visible) enclosing 2.2ha. Rows of possibly four-posters for grain storage. At least five periods of modification/reconstruction. Circa 390 BC bank levelled and new enclosure built of 3.6a visible as the inner rampart and two external banks and ditches. Later an annexe was added to the S, defined by two weak banks and ditches. The mound in the annexe proved to be Roman.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: It has been suggested that the most S of the two lesser outer banks is incomplete.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Detail is outlined in the summary.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The external ditch is up to 10m below the main rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: On NE side high bank to c. 8m high, elsewhere less to 3m, with ditch remnants. Scarp and berm on N and W sides. Possible stone revetment found on inner face of rampart. Defended by natural slope on most of the S side.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: S side defended by natural slope.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Defended by natural slope on most of the south side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank, but rampart may have been revetted in stone. Scarp and berm on NW and W sides.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Possible stone revetment found on inner face of rampart.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Watching brief on development to E of hillfort showed pit and shallow ditch. Possibly buried feature to fort.

Enclosing_Summary: There is a single rampart and ditch and rock cut ditch and bank to W and earthworks at the E end have been confirmed by excavation. The W  bank effectively cuts off the promontory, with steep slopes on the other three sides, and could be interpreted as a possible cross-dyke.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Much has yet to be determined as to the exact boundary of the site.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: No detail known but single rampart and ditch and rock cut ditch and bank to W and earthworks at the E end have been confirmed by excavation. Quadrants here postulated.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Single rampart and ditch and rock-cut ditch and bank to W and earthworks at the E end have been confirmed by excavation.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Rock-cut ditch to the W bank determined. Aerial photographs determined ditch cut some 2m into clay soils. Geophysics found rock cut ditch butt end to 1.5m deep to SE.

Enclosing_Summary: Rampart and ditch 71m long running SW to NE, some 7m wide and up to 1.7m high. Artificially scarped slope and berm to NE. The scarped slope and berm is difficult to detect on the NE side.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Very degraded bank appears to underlie the rampart, extending away for some 15m, its origin unclear.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The shape is D-shaped and difficult to detect in places.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Artificially scarped slope with berm to the NE.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch to NW of the bank.

Enclosing_Summary: Protected by scarp and natural precipitous rock face on the S, the remainder protected by a rampart and outer ditch, the latter as a possible berm on the NE, before disappearing with the rampart 25m from the cliff edge on the SE.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Irregular defences to site with major use of natural rock. Area estimated.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Nature of defences are variable around circuit.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch up to c. 10m wide and 1m-2m deep.

Enclosing_Summary: Steep natural slope only defence on the N and SE sides, and on the W defended by a rampart, but denuded to the N. Inner rampart found to be simple dump of clay, stone and river boulders. Two ditches found by geophysics examined.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site has been extensively damaged through agriculture and development, which makes interpretation difficult on the west and south sides especially.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts do not form a complete circuit because of development; prior to this they would have done so.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of the ramparts and ditches determined by excavation.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Inner rampart found to be simple dump of clay, stone and river boulders. Two ditches found by geophysics examined.

Enclosing_Summary: The line of the former ramparts now visible only as a slight rise with scarp around most of the circuit. It is possible that there might be greater survival where hedge lines cross the ramparts to the E and W and to the S where a lane runs along the line of the ditch. Ramparts quadrants estimated but likely.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Difficulty of interpretation of exact area of fort.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Rampart destruction restricts positive analysis without further site investigation.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: None recorded, but possibly earthen bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly one outer ditch surrounding the site.

Enclosing_Summary: Strong bank and ditch across W end of narrow ridge, naturally steep slopes and bank protection elsewhere.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site is nearly destroyed and is thus seen as a scarp above natural slopes, best to the W and E  ends. Identification therefore difficult.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The rampart is nearly destroyed and can only be seen in small sections at the W and E ends of the site.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The southern single rampart is destroyed making interpretation difficult.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch is nearly gone, with vestigial remains on the N side

Enclosing_Summary: Defences show only as a scarp on the slope of the hill, except on the E and SE sides where the ground falls sharply away. Thus, scarping and artificial strengthening of the natural hillside, with possible palisade, define the site.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Defences seen only as a scarp enclosing the hill. Poor nature of the defences makes interpretation difficult, but not impossible.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Although only seen as a scarp, defences enclose the hill.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: None recorded, but could be a buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: The defences closely follow the contours apart from the N part of the E side, and include a massive inner rampart and ditch and traces of a second bank, beyond which on the E side there is a ditch. The ramparts are complex in construction with possible stone faces and palisade, that to the S with a continuation in an arc to the W around Camp Wood.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The two enclosures and curious shape of the hillfort make a very interesting and complex hillfort. Possibly phased.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Impressive circuit with massive inner rampart and ditch.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Parapets possible on the W and N sides. Dumps over which small limestone rubble deposited recorded.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches in evidence but complex. Separated by berm.

Enclosing_Summary: Double rampart and medial ditch, apart from the SW where there is a single bank to 1.5m high on steep slopes. To NW and NE inner bank strong and up to 2.5m high. There was a possible former enclosure on the NW side. To the SE there is a 1m high outward-facing slope, possibly a ploughed down bank. Counterscarp visible in places.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possible two phases of construction. Proposed by Bowden (2009) as an earlier promontory fort with rampart and ditch, partly confirmed by excavation
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Whilst the main enclosure is enclosed by banks, to the NE, SW and NW, the 'annexe' has steep rocky slopes for the most part over the entire three sides.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavation across rampart and ditch of SE 'annexe' showed it to be early phase of total enclosure and defended by bank and ditch across the promontory neck. Possible palisade slot.

Enclosing_Summary: The single rampart is discontinuous to the W, but intact to the E. The precipitous slope to the N is definition enough, one ditch.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: N line defended by steep slopes with no defence.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Detailed survey of bank and ditch suggested enclosure possibly unfinished.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Detailed investigation of bank and ditch suggested enclosure possibly unfinished.
Enclosing_Gang_Working_Comments: Possible gang working found at 17m intervals as result of topographical survey.

Enclosing_Summary: A single bank with stone faces, with ditch, the former only c. 1m internally, and a small counterscarp bank. The earthworks are made the more imposing by the ditch being up to 11m below the rampart. There are severe gradients on the circuit.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The location on two hills makes the site more complex. Ramparts readily seen. Phased construction.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The single bank and ditch is a complete circuit apart from where quarried away at the extreme SW part of Hollybush Hill.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch up to 11m below the rampart

Enclosing_Summary: The N rampart rises to 2m-3m above level of field; possibly scarped from ridge. E side is similar. W has steep scarp and berm. At S end of W defences berm becomes a ditch with external counterscarp bank. Although ploughed-down the structure of the site is visible.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts much eroded and ploughed-down except to the N. Large site in poor condition, but area definition possible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The detail of the site is visible. At S end of W defences a berm becomes a ditch (faint traces) with external counterscarp bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Faint traces of a ditch to the W.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-Twyn Camp, Brilley, Herefordshire (Pen Twyn Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Double ramparts on W, the inner bank weaker. To S there are no ramparts in evidence, but a hedgeline possibly preserves their location. No ditches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Problem of probably missing southern bank in regard to any area definition. 0.82ha probably an underestimate.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The whole of the S line is missing and now a hedgeline.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: None determined as result of access problems.

Enclosing_Summary: Large, triple-banked, part cropmark. Outer rampart and 40m of inner rampart survive as visible feature partly to E in pasture field.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly three ditches as cropmark only.

Main_Display_Name: Poston Camp, Herefordshire (Lower Park Wood Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Single massive rampart curving from NW-NE with outer ditch; scarping with a berm to the W and S. Precipitous with no defences from NE. Possible of at least a further inner rampart suggested by excavations of 1932-37. Part of the NE and SW sectors have no ramparts.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Massive rampart cuts off the promontory.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Whole of the E side is protected by precipitous slopes.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possibly an earthen bank, with a berm to the W and S.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Possibility of at least a further inner rampart suggested by excavations of 1932-37, but removed by agriculture operations in the 19th century.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch to massive N rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: Double ramparts visible with medial ditch. Outer ditch and counterscarp impressive on W but damaged or gone on the SE. Replaced by berm on steep slope to the N. Outer rampart smaller and mostly destroyed, as is the Inner bank of the inner rampart. The ramparts are variable around the circuit and above an assessment only.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Problems of rampart destruction in area definition.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Outer rampart mostly destroyed, but there is a complete circuit.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch and counterscarp impressive on W, but damaged or gone on SE.

Enclosing_Summary: Widely-spaced ramparts on the E side may be later cultivation terraces or lynchets. On the W the rampart is a dry-built stone wall faced externally - could be conjecture here.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Widely-spaced ramparts on E side may be problematical.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: On W the rampart is a dry-built stone wall faced externally.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: There appears to be no ditches visible.

Enclosing_Summary: The single bank and ditch has been eroded to a steep scarp with a terrace at its foot emphasising the monumentality of the site. This surrounds the site as a degenerate steep scarp. Kenyon suggested that the first rampart was built up from a v-shaped ditch of 32m width and 15m high. Possible pre-rampart palisade.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The rampart and ditch surrounds the site as a degenerate steep scarp.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The rampart and ditch surrounds the site as a degenerate steep scarp, but badly affected by the toxic waste dump to the W.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Initial occupation was probably under the existing bank and protected by a palisade. Possible counterscarp to be determined.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Pre-rampart timber palisade suggested by Kenyon as a result of posthole evidence.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch surrounds the site. Excavation suggested that the first rampart was built up from a v-shaped ditch of 32m width and 15m in height.

Enclosing_Summary: A section across the rampart near the presumed N entrance suggested a rampart some 5.6m high, with possible revetment to the inside face, and ditch. The ditch survives on the W, N and E sides. There is a berm 4m wide to the S and E. A survey by Herefordshire Council in 2012, however, suggested that the crest of the bank is now around 3m above the infilled exterior ditch and questioned whether the earlier 5.6m was accurate. The exact location of the surviving bank is uncertain but thought to survive in places and above estimated.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site area is unknown and estimated.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The exact location of the surviving bank is uncertain, but thought to survive from the SE to SW the rest of the circuit, with slight ditch and no counterscarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank. Berm 4m wide from the SE to SW.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Possible revetment to the inner face of the rampart.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch c 2.5m wide survives on the W, N and E sides, with 1m to the interior.

Enclosing_Summary: Low banks, averaging 3m in height, are now only visible as terraces on the N slope of the hill, but no ditch is visible. There is no evidence on the S side and it has been suggested that the site is unfinished.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Near destruction of site results in problem of area definition.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Banks only visible to the north, nothing visible on S side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earthen bank suggested only. There is no evidence on the S side and it has been suggested that the site is unfinished.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Hills Camp, Ledbury, Herefordshire (Wall Hills, Ledbury)
Enclosing_Summary: The site is characterised by having two enclosures, that to the S being c. 6m higher and separated from the N enclosure by a wet outer ditch. Counterscarp bank. There was a probable ditch with a high steep inner scarp and outer rampart following the natural contours around the outer perimeter of the fort. The ditch is filled and looks like a berm for much of its length. The outer rampart is also fragmentary. The circuit is complete, but its exact nature is not recorded.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Two enclosures - that to W is 3.3ha in area; that to E 8.4ha. No indication of phasing, but possible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earthen bank is conjecture only. The visible berm is the remains of the filled-in outer ditch. There is a counterscarp bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Wet ditch between the two enclosures.  There was a probable ditch with a high steep inner scarp and outer rampart following the natural contours around the outer perimeter of the fort. The ditch is filled and looks like a berm for much of its length.

Enclosing_Summary: A single, massive, rampart and scarping gives height and rises to 12.5m above the ditch to the E, which also has a low counterscarp bank of up to 1.2m.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: An outer ditch remains on the N and E sides.

Enclosing_Summary: Triple ramparts, the outer and inner higher than middle. The inner rampart is strong and up to 3.2m above the ditch bottom, with a counterscarp to 2.6m above ground level.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Circular nature of the site is unusual.

Enclosing_Summary: Defences from the valley below appear massive with three banks on the E and W and two on the N. Two banks 7m-8m high with berm on outer. Two ditches.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts are variable but complete the circuit. Three banks on the E and W and two on the N.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches variable about the site.

Enclosing_Summary: Only the SW part of the site remains. On the NW side of this area there is a two scarp slope visible with inter-spaced berm, with bank remnants to the W and S. Within the enclosure is a slight E to W cross scarp. Most of site destroyed. Possible slight ditch to the SW.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: So little of the site remains, the area of 0.4ha bears little relationship to the actual area of the hillfort.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank fragment. The whole of the NE end destroyed or never completed. Berm on NW.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possible slight ditch to the SW.

Enclosing_Summary: All destroyed, but single ditch confirmed and probably stone-walled site.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Site destroyed and area estimated. Entrance possibly remodelled on more than one occasion suggests phasing and possibly univallate in prehistory.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Site destroyed, but possibly univallate in prehistory.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: No present evidence, site destroyed, but probably stone-walled site.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Single ditch confirmed. Possibly  stone-walled site.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: None. Site destroyed, but former single ditch confirmed by excavation.

Enclosing_Summary: Enclosed by a rampart, ditch and counterscarp some 200m by 120m. the rampart is ploughed down to c. 1m above interior and 5m to the bottom of the ditch, with the counterscarp rising to 1.2m above the ditch. The E and far S sides only have a scarp slope in evidence. A break of slope along the top of the rampart to the N and W could either be later 20th century ploughing, the remnants of a post-medieval hedge bank or possibly a late phase of the defences.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The far S and E sides have only a scarp slope.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The far S and E sides have only a scarp slope. The remainder a bank to 1m above the interior.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch visible on the NW, NE and SW quarters.

Enclosing_Summary: Double ramparts at the N end of the site and covered by additional outwork, but single on the E and W. Multiple ramparts on the S side, but obscured by dense mixed wood planting. Ditches very variable.

The bank is of earth and stone, the top level with the interior and varies in height from c. 0.5m to 1.7m on the N to its highest at 1.5m to 2.4m on the S and SW. The E side has been formed by artificially accentuating the line of the spur with no bank and ditch. The external ditch, which surrounded the interior except on the E,  has been filled in and buried and probably destroyed by the road on the N part of the W side. The line of the ditch can be seen as a slight terrace on the S and SW sides.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Small site, but definitely a hillfort.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts surround the circuit except on the E where the slope is steepest and no major defence required.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Traces of a bank except on the E side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The external ditch, which surrounded the interior except on the E,  has been filled in and buried and probably destroyed by the road on the N part of the W side. The line of the ditch can be seen as a slight terrace on the S and SW sides.

Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart rising to nearly 2m from the interior, and dropping between c. 5m-6m+ to the deep surrounding ditch, which continues around the headland as a berm of c. 2. width. A simple entrance crosses the N bank at its E end. The bank was possibly originally a cross-dyke cutting off the spur, with the entrance cut later in prehistory and the slopes scarped to form the present enclosure.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The N bank was possibly originally a cross-dyke cutting off the spur.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Deep surrounding ditch continues around the headland as a berm of c. 2. width.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The deep surrounding ditch continues around the headland as a berm of c. 2 m width.

Enclosing_Summary: A possible bank and ditch are visible on aerial photographs on the E side, but difficult to see on the ground apart from a possible break of slope. A possible enhanced gully on the W side may be defences and a slight change of slope to the S may also be defences.  The precipitous N appears to have no defences.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The enclosed are has yet to be determined.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The precipitous N appears to have no defences.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: A ditch is now a buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by a scarp slope around 1.6m high, with a steep natural slope on the SW. The NW end encloses a natural knoll and here there are races of an external ditch. The apparent ditch to the SE could be a natural gully.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of an external ditch to the NW. The apparent ditch to the SE could be a natural gully.

Enclosing_Summary: Three massive ramparts and ditches in evidence, apart from at the NW where a single rampart and ditch with counterscarp defend the steepest side. Use made of natural outcrops enhance and included in the circuit in the NW sector and on the S side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Three massive ramparts and ditches in evidence, apart from at the NW where a single rampart and ditch with counterscarp defend the steepest side.

Enclosing_Summary: Roughly oval in shape, with up to five massive ramparts up to 7m in height on the N side where the slopes are less steep; each with an outer ditch. Possible quarry scoops in the interior of the innermost rampart. On the S and E sides there are two ramparts with medial ditch where the slopes are steeper.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Superb circuit of up to five ramparts.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Each of the up to five ramparts has an outer ditch.

Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart built on the steepest S,E and W slopes and double ramparts and ditches on the less steep N edge of the hill. In places inner bank 11.6 m high. Ditch cutting across site may be an earlier rampart to smaller enclosure.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch cutting across site may be an earlier rampart to smaller enclosure.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Caradoc, Clun, Shropshire (Caer Caradoc, Chapel Lawn; Gaer Ditches)
Enclosing_Summary: Two banks and ditches for most of circuit, but outer bank absent on the S where there is a counterscarp and on the W a third bank and ditch is separated from second ditch by a level space giving added protection to the S flank of the entrance. the ramparts have broad flat tops. Phased construction of dry-stone wall faced ramparts of flat siltstone flags, later heightened and widened by dump construction.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Phased construction of dry-stone wall faced ramparts of flat siltstone flags, later heightened and widened by dump construction.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Number of ramparts vary around circuit. No details of phasing.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Two banks and ditches for most of circuit, but outer bank absent on the south where there is a counterscarp and on the west a third bank and ditch is separated from second ditch by a level space giving added protection to the south flank of the entrance. Phased construction of dry-stone wall faced ramparts of flat siltstone flags, later heightened and widened by dump construction. Ramparts have broad flat tops.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Phased construction of dry-stone wall faced ramparts of flat siltstone flags, later heightened and widened by dump construction. Ramparts have broad flat tops.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Up to three ditches in evidence.

Enclosing_Summary: Main inner scarped rampart (formerly a stone wall?) follows the crest of the slopes and uses natural rock on the SE. 25 m from this is an outer  additional bank for most of the circuit constructed from an internal quarry ditch. Third defensive bank on shallower S side. The inner rampart is 12 m wide and up to 1.7 in height, enclosing an area 375 m by 70 m. The outer rampart is 10 m below around the N part of the site, 10 m wide and o.5 m high and with an internal ditch 0.5 m deep. The ditch reappears at the SW end with the third rampart to the SW.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The number of ramparts vary around the circuit.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Main inner scarped rampart (formerly a stone wall?) follows the crest of the slopes and uses natural rock on the south-east. 25 m from this is an outer  additional bank for most of the circuit constructed from an internal quarry ditch. Third defensive bank on shallower southern side. The inner rampart is 12 m wide and up to 1.7 in height, enclosing an area 375 m x 70 m. The outer rampart is 10 m below around the N part of the site, 10 m wide and o.5 m high and with an internal ditch 0.5 m deep. The ditch reappears at the SW end with the tird rampart to the SW.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Main inner scarped rampart formerly a stone wall?

Enclosing_Summary: The S is bounded on the W and SW by steep and rocky cliffs falling c. 100 m to the river. A massive earth and stone rampart cuts off the promontory on the E and NE, some 14 m wide and up to 1.7 m high internally and standing 4.5 m above an outer ditch 8 m wide and 1.2 m deep. The rampart stops abruptly at the S end at the edge of the natural slope, and it is here that the entrance was located. To the N the rampart fades out at the natural slopes, or may not have been completed.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Ramparts cut off the promontory on the E side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possibly earth and stone bank. To the N the rampart fades out at the natural slopes, or may not have been completed.

Enclosing_Summary: A bank and outer ditch of earth and stone, both reduced by ploughing, surround the site. The ditch is can be seen to 0.2 m to the S and on the NW side a steep rock-cut face is visible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone bank and rock-cut face to ditch to the NW.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch is can be seen to 0.2 m to the S and on the NW side a steep rock-cut face is visible.

Enclosing_Summary: Slopes are very steep to the river on the E and N and here the ramparts form a steep scarp, mutilated in places to the S. It appears that the hillfort was of phased construction, Phase I being a roughly rectangular site some 130m by120m and possibly enclosing c. 1.4ha, including the summit of the spur (now occupied by a water tank) and the gently sloping E slopes and with a NW entrance. Later in Phase II, the site was extended, seemingly with two lines if bank and ditch near to the entrance which may have been remodelled with passageway and inturns. The site has been mutilated, especially on the SW side.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The area is not definite. Two phased construction.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts in each quadrant, but not complete, as site mutilated, especially on SW side where buildings of Calcot Farm.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The field track has exposed a dump earthen bank with a few stones.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly two ditches. There are two lines of bank and ditch near to the NW entrance and there may be evidence of a slight ditch to the S.

Enclosing_Summary: There are two principal ramparts separated by a ditch, the outer faces of the ramparts surviving as scarps following the contours. This ditch has been largely filled, but survives as a buried feature. On the NW an outer ditch with external rampart survives and this is similar on the S, but with a terrace or infilled ditch. The E ramparts have been almost destroyed, otherwise the condition is essentially good.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: A small site but with substantial ramparts.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The ramparts are almost destroyed on the E side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch between the two principal ramparts has been largely filled, but survives as a buried feature. On the NW an outer ditch with external rampart survives and this is similar on the S but with a terrace or infilled ditch.

Enclosing_Summary: The bank reaches up to 1m in height and 10m on the W, where it is best preserved, with an outer ditch 6m wide and 0.5m deep. Elsewhere it is reduced to an outward facing scarp with no ditch visible, although this is now probably a buried feature. Both the bank and the ditch have been subject to ploughing and to the E the former has been mostly levelled.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Despite damage, the outine of the fort forms a complete circuit.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The bank reaches up to 1 m in height and 10 m on the W, where it is best preserved. Elsewhere it is reduced to an outward facing scarp.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch visible in places as shallow depressions on the W, but forms a buried feature elsewhere.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Ring, Gorsty Bank, Shropshire (Gorsty Bank)
Enclosing_Summary: The site has been almost levelled, but formerly there would have been a single rampart of stone.The rampart is now just a break of slope over much of circuit and were possibly robbed in the post-medieval period to form adjacent hedge banks. The probable ditch is not visible, but now a buried feature.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The site has been almost levelled.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The site has been almost levelled.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The site has been almost levelled, but formerly there would have been a single rampart.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: A clearance cairn outside the NE entrance constructed from robbed rampart material suggests that the rampart would have been of stone construction.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The probable ditch is not visible, but now a buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: The site is roughly triangular in shape measuring 74m by 60m, maximum use made of the natural topography with minimum use made of artificial defences. To the W and NW are precipitous slopes, requiring no defence, whilst on the lesser slopes of the NE and SE are substantial earthworks sited roughly at right-angles to each other. The N rampart is better preserved and rises to 2m on its outer face; that to the S being ploughed-down and dispersed and rising to only 0.5m. The ditches are now only traces in places, most being now buried features.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The W and NW sides are precipitous natural slopes.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditches are now only traces in places, most being now buried features.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Hill, Oak Hill, Shropshire (Oak Hill)
Enclosing_Summary: Single bank on across the ridge the S side, the natural approach along the ridge, 8m wide and up to 3.5m above an outer ditch 5m wide and 1.2m deep. On the W and N the natural defences of very steep slopes are strengthened by an artificial steep scarp slope 3m high and outer berm 3m wide.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The precipitous slopes on the W and N make assessment of area difficult.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Although the S side has the promontory cut off by a rampart, the steep natural defences on the W and N have artificial strengthening.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Although the S side has the promontory cut off by a rampart, the steep natural defences on the W and N have artificial strengthening and therefore are included as above.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The outer ditch is 5m wide and 1.2 m deep.

Enclosing_Summary: The N side has a bank to 2.1m high, with external ditch and across the S end are three small banks with internal ditches where the slopes are steepest. To the E and W, on the edge of the slope, there are no defences.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: No defences on the E and W.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The N side has a bank to 2.1 m high, with external ditch and across the S end are three small banks with internal ditches where the slopes are steepest.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The N side has a bank with external ditch and across the S end are three small banks with internal ditches where the slopes are steepest.

Enclosing_Summary: The defences are bivallate on the NW and SE and trivallate on the NE and SW, separated by ditches. Only parts of the site are visible. Some masonry, stone faces, is visible in the ditches at the entrances.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The main enclosure is estimated only at c. 3.6 ha.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Only parts of the site are visible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Some masonry is visible in the ditches at the entrances.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditches are visible only as depressions or sloping terraces.

Enclosing_Summary: On E side the impressive, part tree-clad rampart is up to 5.5m in height with a 4m wide ditch and counterscarp bank. On the N side where the slope is steepest, the rampart is slight or missing. Excavation showed three phases of rampart construction: Phase I showed the earliest defences to be timber-laced of c. 390 BC, replaced in Phase II by a smaller stone revetted bank and later in Phase III by the the present massive defences.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Multiple phased construction. Phase I, the earliest, defences to timber-laced of c. 390 BC, replaced in Phase II by smaller stone revetted bank and later in Phase III by present massive defences.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: On the N side where the slope is steepest, the rampart is slight or absent. Although seemingly phased annexes to W, site defined as one entity for quadrant purposes.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earthen and stone construction to Phase III rampart. Counterscarp bank surrounds site. Some erosion on the N rampart top exposing dry-stone walling.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Timber-lacing to Phase I rampart. Stone revetted bank to Phase II and earthen and stone construction to Phase III rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: The fort is defended on the N and W by a bank and ditch, on the NE by a rampart on the crest of the slope, and on the S by a precipitous hillside. The rampart is strongest on the N, where it rises 2 m + above the interior and falls some 9m+ to a deep 3m ditch.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: S is protected by a precipitous hillside.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch on N side smoothed down by ploughing.

Enclosing_Summary: Only remnants left are ragged remains of stone rampart, now reduced to a stony scarp, for some 100m in length and to 2.7m in height, in the SE quadrant. Elsewhere, the site has been either quarried away to the NW or dumped upon by later spoil dumps from quarry and mine.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The majority of the site has been destroyed and the whole site footprint cannot be determined.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The only remnants of the circuit are in the SE quadrant, but it is possible to ascertain that the site was roughly ovoid in shape circling the hill and quite strong in character.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Probably a stone-walled site from remaining evidence on site.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Any evidence of ditches destroyed, but probably there was no ditch.

Enclosing_Summary: The ramparts of loose stone and small boulders have been generally destroyed and tumbled downslope, but are best on the N, west and SE where up to 6 m wide. The mutilated remains of a ditch remain on the SW side. To the SW there is a possible outer bank where the slope is less steep on the lower extension of the ridge. Probably a stone-walled site rather than dump construction. A simple break through the rampart on the W near a very steep slope is a possible original entrance.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The tumbled nature of the ramparts make definite measurements difficult to interpret.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Possible outer stone bank on the SW.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Mutilated remains if a ditch on the SW side.

Enclosing_Summary: The site is defined by a simple bank 9m wide and up to 2m high with ditch 4m wide and 0.5m deep. The ramparts are most massive on the S where the approach is better. A possible small earlier or interior enclosure of c. 0.1ha has been suggested on the W side. On the E the bank is discontinuous. The rampart has been truncated on the N side by a forestry road, but a possible outer rampart has been suggested here to the N of this track.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Rampart truncated on the N side.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The might be a possible outer bank on the N affected by a forestry track.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Good evidence of a ditch to 0.5 m in depth.

Enclosing_Summary: The main enclosure, created  by cutting into the hillside, has a single flat topped rampart and ditch encloses 1.1ha, apart from on the E where the slope is at its most precipitous and evidence of only a slight scarp, and with a slight counterscarp bank to the NW and upper and lower berms to the W. Possible evidence of vitrification. Evidence of a counterscarp bank on the NW. Simple gap in the rampart on the S, over a causeway/ ditch, reaches a 1.7ha elongated annexe or addition, defended on the S and W by a bank up to 6m high, with intermittent berm and counterscarp bank and ditch to the S corner. As with the main enclosure, the E is well defended by precipitous slopes.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Evidence of slight scarp only on the E where the slope is precipitous.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: A main enclosure with single rampart and ditch encloses 1.1 ha apart from on the east where the slope is at its most precipitous and evidence of only a slight scarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible evidence of vitrification, counterscarp banks and intermittent berms.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Rampart and ditch to both main and annexe enclosures.

Enclosing_Summary: A single bank surrounds the site, on the SE and SW sides up to c. 2m with an outer ditch. No ditch can be seen on the other sides, but probably existed in prehistory as there appears to be no quarry ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: An outer ditch exists on the SE and SW sides, not visible on the other sides, but probably existed in prehistory.

Enclosing_Summary: The earth and stone rampart is strongest on the exposed NW side, but is lower and ploughed out or reduced on the other sides, where slopes are precipitous, to little more than an outer facing scarp. There is a possible counterscarp bank on the SE and SW. The outer ditch averages 8m in width and has a depth of 1.2m on the NW, being completely ploughed-out to the NE.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Small site but very strong position.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The earth and stone rampart is strongest on the exposed NW side, but is lower and ploughed out or reduced on the other sides, where slopes are precipitous, to little more than an outer facing scarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone bank recorded as surface evidence. Possible counterscarp bank on SE and SW.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The outer ditch averages 8m in width and has a depth of 1.2m on the NW, being completely ploughed-out to the NE.

Main_Display_Name: Haughmond Hill Camp, Shropshire (Haughmond Castle; Castle Earthwork)
Enclosing_Summary: Earth and stone rampart survives on the NW, S and SE sides and generally discontinuous. The NE side is open where there was a former marsh as protection. S rampart possibly never completed where meets the marsh. The rampart rises to nearly 2m on the N. Extensive use of natural rock features on the circuit. Most of the W rampart may in fact be natural. Infilled ditch on the SE and NW sides.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: No rampart to the NW where former marsh.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Earth and stone rampart survives on the NW, S and SE sides and generally discontinuous. The NE side is open where there was a former marsh as protection.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone ramparts. S side possibly unfinished where meets former marsh.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Infilled ditch on the SE and NW sides.

Enclosing_Summary: Earthwork remains of a substantial bank and ditch with possible counterscarp on the N, S and W sides. To the N the degraded bank appears on the line of a hedgerow. To E nothing is visible and it has been suggested that this could either indicate that the site was unfinished or that the E ramparts were removed by post-medieval common edge settlement present on the site. A modern pond has been dug though the line of the possible ditch to the NE part of the site.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earthen bank where survives. It is possible that the site was unfinished. Possible counterscarp on the N, S and W sides.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: A modern pond has been dug though the line of the possible ditch to the NE part of the site.

Enclosing_Summary: Moderate, low single rampart on S and W, later incorporated into construction of Offa's Dyke and gaps here modern. On N and E c. 300m of double and triple (in places) ramparts visible. Pipe trench excavation produced loose limestone rubble construction and vertically faced at rear.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Pipe trench excavation produced loose limestone rubble construction and vertically faced at rear.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Total number of ditches not defined.

Enclosing_Summary: Strong defences, with single turf-covered rampart to nearly 3m on the E and an outer rock-cut ditch to 1.5m in depth and between 5m-8m in width, are in evidence around the circuit. There could be traces of a counterscarp bank.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The boundary of the site is easily discernible over the complete circuit.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Good evidence around the complete circuit.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Strong defences, with single turf-covered rampart. There could be traces of a counterscarp bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: An outer rock-cut ditch to 1.5m in depth and between 5m-8m in width, is in evidence around the circuit.

Enclosing_Summary: There are two ramparts with external ditch, except on the precipitous NW side where there is a single small bank or straight side rampart with evidence of breastwork or low wall on its top. The inner rampart is steep sided with a narrow top, the outer gentler and stepped in places. To the SW the site is reinforced by two additional banks separated by a ditch, which could be late Bronze Age cross-dykes incorporated into the circuit. Rock-cut faces are visible in the medial ditch at the SW and NE ends of the site. Up to three ditches.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The number of banks vary about the site.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of breastwork or low wall on top of small rampart on NW.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Up to three ditches. Rock-cut faces are visible in the medial ditch at the SW and NE ends of the site.

Enclosing_Summary: The site is enclosed for much of the circuit by five ramparts and ditches, which rise to seven on the W side. Outer bank may be a counterscarp. Excavations by Varley in 1939-40 showed late Bronze Age origins to the site when protected by a palisade and from c. 600 BC the formidable defences were constructed in phases. This began with a single stone-revetted rampart later added to by successive circuits of defence. Finally, the great W entrance was re-modelled and the massive ramparts of today constructed.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Outer bank may be a counterscarp.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavations by Varley in 1939-40 showed late Bronze Age origins to the site when protected by a palisade and from c. 600 BC the formidable defences were constructed in phases. This began with a single stone-revetted rampart later added to by successive circuits of defence. Finally, the great W entrance was re-modelled and the massive ramparts of today constructed.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditches vary about the circuit.

Enclosing_Summary: To the S and E are two ramparts with external ditches, the outer now a buried feature. To the NE, where the slopes are steeper, is a single rampart and buried ditch. On the NW the sheer sandstone cliff is adequate defence with no rampart. The S ramparts have been reduced to just two scarps. The ramparts appear to be of dump rubble near the entrance and inner rampart to the S revetted with loose sandstone blocks.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Site shows several phases of construction dividing the fort into two areas - an area of substantial defences to the W with two ramparts and ditch enclosing the highest point of the site to c. 1ha and an area to the E defined by the existing defences.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: NW side sheer cliffs, thus not requiring rampart defence.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Ramparts univallate to the north where steeper slopes and bivallate to the south. On the NW side are sheer cliffs not requiring rampart defence.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Small exposure on the N side of the entrance showed dump rubble construction.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavations in the S showed that the outer rampart was revetted with loose sandstone blocks.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The outer ditch is now a buried feature. Vertical faces of the rock-cut ditch can be seen at the entrance.

Enclosing_Summary: The earthworks have been gradually removed by ploughing over the past 20-30 years and are now only cropmarks, but some earthworks remain to the S. Here the single bank is now reduced to c. 0.2m in height with frontal ditch around 4m in width, now infilled and a buried feature. To the N there are two additional banks, interspaced with two principal ditches, also c. 4m in width and now infilled as buried features. Ploughing has reduced these N banks to mere cropmarks. The natural glacial gully has been incorporated into the defensive circuit with a ditch dug along its base.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Three banks of N circuit reduced to cropmarks.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The three banks of the northern circuit have been reduced to cropmarks by ploughing.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Ditches investigated, showed to be c. 2m in depth with waterlogged base.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches investigated, showed to be c. 2m in depth with waterlogged base. It is possible that there might be a third ditch as a buried feature to be determined.

Enclosing_Summary: The ramparts appear to be of dump construction of yellow boulder clay of inner rampart up to 2m high, traces of a medial ditch, 7m wide and to 0.3m deep on the W and NE sides, and an outer rampart, up to 4.5m high, and outer ditch. The E to S side has been mostly destroyed by a forestry road. On the weaker W side, is a third outer rampart, 9m wide, and up to 2m high externally, with the inner ditch 6m wide and up to 0.3m deep. A rock outcrop on the NW coincides with the outer rampart.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: There is a marked contrast between the size of the whole site footprint and the interior area. Three pre-rampart phases were found in a trench through the middle rampart.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: E to S defences destroyed by a forestry road.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: E to S defences destroyed by a forestry road.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Rampart of dump construction. Earlier Neolithic palisade found by excavation with widely-spaced postholes and pebble surfaces associated with post-built structures beneath the middle rampart and Neolithic rubbish pit.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches rising to three in W. E ditches destroyed and ditches generally buried features. Medial ditch between inner and outer rampart is buried and has been mistaken for a berm.

Enclosing_Summary: The site is thought to have been probably unfinished because of the lack of ramparts visible on the E side. Elsewhere on the other three sides of the triangular shaped site, is a bank with stone,  and ditch with intermittent counterscarp bank to 1.5m external height. The main bank is c. 12m wide and 3.1m to the base of an outer ditch, 6m wide. The E termination of both N and S banks is ragged and the ditches become progressively shallower.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: A possible stone rampart is unconfirmed. Intermittent counterscarp bank to 1.5m external height. The site is thought to have been probably unfinished because of the lack of ramparts visible on the E side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch to bank is c. 6m wide.

Main_Display_Name: Ratlinghope Hill Camp, Shropshire (Ratlinghope Hill; Stitt Hill)
Enclosing_Summary: To N there is a cross-bank rampart 10m wide and 0.9m high, with associated ditch 5m wide and 0.9m deep. The rampart follows the shoulder for 30m on the E side and 40m on the W, with scarping to the S angle. There is a major gap on the E side,
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: There is a major gap in the ramparts/scarp on the E.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: There is a major gap in the ramparts/scarp on the east.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The associated ditch is 5m wide and 0.9m deep.

Enclosing_Summary: The banks have been much reduced by ploughing and destroyed on the SW where the house is located. Basically it was a double-banked and ditched enclosure, some 55m in diameter internally and 110m externally. On the E side the outer ditch remains virtually intact, but trampled by cattle, 8m-9m wide, but only 0.3m deep at most. The inner ditch on the E is now only a slight scarp, whilst that on the W little remains. On the NW the outer ditch is now the course of a stream and hedge bank, which may be the site of the rampart. Only fragments of the bank remains in places.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts almost destroyed. Formerly two surrounded the enclosure.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: In 1990 a small excavation in advance of farmhouse extension found clay deposits possibly being part of the inner bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: On the E side the outer ditch remains virtually intact, but trampled by cattle, 8m-9m wide but only 0.3m deep at most. The inner ditch on the E is now only a slight scarp, whilst that on the W little remains. On the NW the outer ditch is now the course of a stream and hedge bank, which may be the site of the rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: To the W and NW a substantial linear rampart, some 10m wide and now 2.5m high on its W face and 1m on its E, has been constructed. A ditch, 6m wide and 1.3m deep, runs along the rampart base on its W side. At the S end the rampart links with the natural cliff face. To the N it curves to the E before fading out at the steepening NE slope. Full use made of the natural cliffs on the S, E and NE sides.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Full use made of the natural cliffs on the S, E and NE sides.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: An old cutting, c. 1m wide, across the bank and ditch, may be associated with the past excavations at The Roveries Hill Camp, but there are no records of this available.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: A ditch, 6m wide and 1.3m deep, runs along the rampart base on its W side.

Enclosing_Summary: The fort makes full use of the topography with a single substantial dry-stone revetted rampart surviving on the SW and part of the NW and SE sides. This averages 3.8m in height on the outside, with ditch 5m wide by 0.2m deep. Around the NE corner the perimeter is now defined by the top of precipitous natural slopes. The construction of the rampart is clearly seen in trenches left open from excavations undertaken in 1935-39 and 1960-63.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Phased construction to NW entrance and possibly to hillfort. The excavations of 1960-63 found evidence of an earlier phase and unfinished causewayed ditch partly under the rampart.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Around the NE corner the perimeter is now defined by the top of precipitous natural slopes.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: A single substantial drystone revetted rampart survives on the SW and part of the NW and SE sides. This averages 3.8 m in height on the outside, with ditch 5 m wide x 0.2 m deep. Around the NE corner the perimeter is now defined by the top of precipitous natural slopes.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The dry-stone revetted construction of the rampart is clearly seen in trenches left open from excavations undertaken in 1935-39 and 1960-63. To E of the entrance a berm or terrace has been cut into the hillside 20m below the top of the rampart and extending around the N quarter and possibly constructed to strengthen the entrance.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: The dry-stone revetted construction of the rampart is clearly seen in trenches left open from excavations undertaken in 1935-39 and 1960-63. To E of the entrance a berm or terrace has been cut into the hillside 20m below the top of the rampart and extending around the N quarter and possibly constructed to strengthen the entrance. The excavations of 1960-63 found evidence of an earlier phase and unfinished causewayed ditch partly under the rampart.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditch is 5m wide by 0.2m deep. The excavations of 1960-63 found evidence of an earlier phase and unfinished causewayed ditch partly under the rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: The larger mound, 220m by 250m, at only 92m O.D., is surrounded by a single irregular circuit of scarp cut on the N, W and S sides and bank on the E, and enclosing some 3.1ha. To the N, the smaller mound, at 130m by 100m,  also has a single rampart on the S, W and E sides, enclosing c. 0.5ha. Both of these enclosures are connected by a gravel, stone possibly revettted causeway 120m in length, which is also linked with the rising ground to the S by another causeway some 240m in length. This is now cut through by a stream which drains The Berth Pool, No ditches visible.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: There are two enclosed areas - the larger of 3.1ha, the smaller of 0.5ha, connected by a causeway. Three main levels of occupation.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: There are two enclosed areas - the larger of 3.1ha, the smaller of 0.5ha, connected by a causeway.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: There are two enclosed areas - the larger of 3.1 ha, the smaller of 0.5 ha, connected by a causeway.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Ramparts composed of gravel and stone. The rampart show evidence of dump construction on the N side.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Gelling found the ramparts to be composed of gravel and stone with evidence of revetment to the causeway and relatively large and rough facing stones at the base of the outer face of the rampart of the larger enclosure possibly protecting the bank from the lake outside.

Main_Display_Name: The Burgs, Shropshire (The Buries; Bayston Hill)
Enclosing_Summary: Much affected by housing development up to the 1970' and as a result the complex banks of the S/SW corner have either been destroyed or are situated within domestic curtilages. Apart from here the fort is bivallate for most of the circuit and on most of the N side the defences are still in place, though ploughed in part. The absence of a rampart at the N corner is probably due to quarrying, Quarrying has also affected the E side, and the outer bank here may not be entirely original and is a field bank following the original line. A series of trenches as a result of development in the 1970's showed a red clay subsoil and the rampart to be composed of yellow/grey sandy soil of possibly redeposited Boulder Clay with a concentration of largish stones stacked up almost vertically, but not faced; a possible but unproven revetment. An exposure on the E side was similar. Between these stacks were levels of charred and possible horizontal timbers suggesting a form of burnt timber-lacing or timber framing.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Housing development mitigates against a final area definition.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: W/SW side part obliterated by development.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: W/SW side part obliterated by development, but elsewher circuit mostly bivallate.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: A series of trenches as a result of development in the 1970's showed a red clay subsoil and the rampart to be composed of yellow/grey sandy soil of possibly redeposited Boulder Clay with a concentration of largish stones stacked up almost vertically, but not faced; a possible but unproven revetment. An exposure on the E side was similar. Between these stacks were levels of charred and possible horizontal timbers suggesting a form of burnt timber-lacing or timber framing.

Main_Display_Name: The Ditches, Mogg Forest, Shropshire (Larden Ditches; Mogg Ditches; The Rings; Wynbury Castle; Larden Castle)
Enclosing_Summary: The three lines of well-preserved and widely-spaced defence are strongest on the weaker NE, E and S sides and here the main rampart is massive, being 15m wide and rising to 5.6m externally. The flat topped middle rampart is 16m wide and rises to 2.2m with a small bank or creat of 0.4m high along its outer edge. The outer bank, of some 12m width, rises to 2.3m in height, with a gradual inner and steep outer slope with a narrow crest. Hillwash has reduced the inner bank to a scarp on the NW and the middle and inner ramparts have been damaged near the SW entrance. Ditches (3) now mostly as buried features, but traces of outer ditch on the NE and SW sides.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of a berm in places.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches now mostly as buried features, but traces of outer ditch on the NE and SW sides.

Enclosing_Summary: Two weak banks have a medial and outer ditch facing W uphill and have the appearance of a small cross ridge dyke. The outer ditch is almost buried and the medial ditch now only 0.3m deep, although 4m-5m wide.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Two weak banks have a medial and outer ditch facing W uphill and have the appearance of a small cross ridge dyke.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The outer ditch is almost buried and the medial ditch now only 0.3m deep, although 4m-5m wide.

Enclosing_Summary: The elongated rectangle is only some 91m long by 36m at its waist. Fairly strong cross-ridge banks with outer ditch at each end (SW and NE) of the narrow ridge (some 15m-20m wide), with scarping on the flanks largely enhancing the natural slopes of the hill and with a counterscarp at the SW end. Cross-ridge banks defends the ends of the site.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earthen bank. Counterscarp at E end.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch at each end (SW and NE) of the narrow ridge site.

Enclosing_Summary: A cross-dyke some 100m long crosss the the ridge from the NW to SE, SW of the trig point on the summit of the hill, as a well-defined and and partly rock-cut ditch c. 8m wide and 1.5m deep and with an internal bank c. 0.6wide and 0.9m high. The ditch fades downslope and at the NW side is a slight scarp running along the slopes to beyond the trig point and to return around the NE side of the summit.

There are two enclosures, reflecting the phased construction and occupation of the site. Unusually for a hillfort, an outer enclosure of c. 8ha, with mainly double earth and stone ramparts and infilled ditch, is thought to have been constructed first. This shows today as a series of terraces to 5m in height utilising the rock outcrops and extending around the hillsides and dates to around 7th-5th centuries BC, lasting till around 5th-4th centuries BC. An inner enclosure of 3.5ha with single rampart, ditch and counterscarp was then constructed and the outer enclosure abandoned, but then to be reoccupied about 100 years later. The bank of the inner enclosure, with quarry ditch, was initially of clay-stone construction with external dry-stone retaining wall, but was later remodelled with an enlarged rampart and a timber palisade. The ramparts are most substantial near to the entrances, elsewhere now just low mounds.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The inner enclosure encloses 3.5ha and is of later date than the outer enclosure.  Excavations by S.C. Stanford 1973 found post-built structures with three to four rebuilding phases.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The structure of the ramparts was determined by excavation, but an earthen and stone bank and counterscarp are evident.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Unusually for a hillfort, an outer enclosure of c. 8ha, with mainly double earth and stone ramparts and infilled ditch, is thought to have been constructed first. An inner enclosure of 3.5ha with single rampart, ditch and counterscarp was then constructed and the outer enclosure abandoned and later re-occupied. The bank of the inner enclosure with quarry ditch was initially of clay-stone construction with external dry-stone retaining wall, but was later remodelled with an enlarged rampart and a timber palisade.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: The ditches are variable around the site.

Enclosing_Summary: Despite being nearly lost on the S side to abandoned quarrying, surprisingly good stone ramparts remain over part of the circuit. Phase I had an earth rampart revetted in front with a timber palisade, a line of post-holes being found. There is a single stone rampart to the N and E of the hill up to 13m in width and up to 2.4m on the exterior face. which shows as a tumble of scree. To small sections of turf covered stone bank remain on the S side between the two quarries that here cut into the enclosure. No ditch is visible.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Two phases of construction found by O'Neil. Large site much affected by quarrying make the actual enclosed area difficult to define exactly.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The site probably formed a continuous circuit, though the present rampart runs into scree below a precipitous crag at the western end of the site, but what was the original form here is open to conjecture.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: There is a single stone rampart to the north and east of the hill up to 13 m in width and up to 2.4 m on the exterior face. which shows as a tumble of scree. To small sections of turf covered stone bank remain on the south side between the two quarries that here cut into the enclosure.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: There is a single stone rampart to the north and east of the hill up to 13m in width and up to 2.4m on the exterior face. which shows as a tumble of scree. To small sections of turf covered stone bank remain on the south side between the two quarries that here cut into the enclosure.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Phase I had an earth rampart revetted in front with a timber palisade, a line of post-holes being found. The entrance was incurved with probable bridge and turfed walk over. A period of decay was followed in Phase II by a heightened rampart faced with drystone walling, its collape shown today as scree lying outside the foot of the bank. There were elaborate guard chambers at the gate.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Camp, Kynnersley, Shropshire (The Wall; Kinnersley Wall)
Enclosing_Summary: Rubble and Boulder Clay inner bank, with possible stone retaining walls, is almost intact, apart from where a modern road crosses the summit of the rise, but it is much ploughed and spread, averaging 2.5m wide and 1.5m high on the N. This inner rampart is surrounded by a complex of up to five close-set banks, with ditches, strongest on the NW side where the ground is slightly higher than on the SE, up to c. 1m high now and 6m-12m wide, with evidence of considerable re-modelling. The outer bank possibly circled the perimeter, apart, it seems to the SE, but it has long stretches where it is destroyed on the NW and W sides. These banks are all much fragmented and ploughed down, some now buried and difficult to interpret, but would have formed a very formidable obstacle in prehistory. The exact number of banks on each quarter is difficult to assess, but there are up to five in each quarter apart from the SE.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Excavations by J.A. Pagett of the Wrekin Archaeological Group in 1962-65 across the defences showed four periods of construction and how complex the site is, but no dating evidence.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: The banks are composed of rubble and Boulder Clay with stone retaining walls. Small excavation by T.C. Canrill in 1919 through inner rampart found clay and rubble rampart faced with stone retaining slabs.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Up to five ditches, most now buried features.

Enclosing_Summary: Two lines of bank and ditch have a counterscarp bank on the W and NW sides. In the SE sector the rampart is spread and reduced to only a scarp. Geophysical survey of 1999, although being generally inconclusive, found remnants of the inner bank in several places in the interior.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Good circuit of two ramparts plus counterscarp bank to W and NW.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Counterscarp bank to the W and NW.

Enclosing_Summary: All but the S half of the interior, including the inner bank, has been levelled as result of ploughing and afforestation in 1935. Formerly defended by two principal banks with medial ditch, now infilled. Towards the NE, where the slope is less, the ramparts may have been more elaborate with an entrance here and possibly four low banks. The two ramparts are generally reduced to an outward facing scarp.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The area is difficult to assess because of the extensive damage to the site.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The area is difficult to assess because of the extensive damage to the site, but formerly covered the circuit.

Enclosing_Summary: Small univallate contour fort of 3.2ha now lying in woodland. It comprises a bank, an outer ditch and counterscarp and an outwork to the W where the defences are weakest. It is roughly triangular in plan and measures approximately 542m NE-SW by 385m transversely including the outwork lying 55m to the W. The enclosing works of the main enclosure are of dump construction standing over 2m high from the bottom of the ditch, with a marked counterscarp in the NE.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: It was observed by Wood (1958) that along the easiest approach to the hillfort in the region of the south-west corner the enclosing works were at their strongest and appear to have been strengthened by the addition of an outer bank on the side of easiest access.  Conversely on the south overlooking the steepest slope and coinciding with springs and a boggy area the banks weak with the inner bank replaced by a scarped slope.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: The bank is of univallate dump construction with a marked counterscarp in the north-east and approximately 3m deep ditch with an internal step where excavated.  A further earthwork follows the western side along the weakest part of the defences.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavation in the west provided evidence for a bank which was possibly reinforced with a timber palisade and later strengthened by a flint wall
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: 3m deep ditch with an internal step

Main_Display_Name: Bussock Camp, West Berkshire (Bussock Wood Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: The defences are univallate in the N and W facing steeper ground and bivallate elsewhere where the approach is more accessible. The banks are spaced approximately 17m apart with a deep ditch between.  A further short length of ditch has been recorded in the east. The ramparts follow the steep natural slope in the N and W.
Enclosing_Gang_Working_Comments: Further short length of ditch recorded in the E.

Enclosing_Summary: Univallate with a steep outward facing scarp and slight outer ditch. Traces of a counterscarp bank in places. The top of the rampart in the N is approximately 5m above the ditch bottom.  Slight banks extend from the NW entrance as 'barbican-like' features (Payne 2006:45).  Beyond these In the W a further 120m length of ditch cuts across the ridge.  Both are associated with a hollow way.
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Univallate with a steep outward facing scarp and slight outer ditch.  In places there are traces of a counterscarp bank. The top of the rampart on the north side is approximately 5m above the ditch bottom.  Slight banks extend from the north-west entrance as 'barbican-like' features (Payne 2006:45).  Beyond these In the west a further 120 m length of ditch cuts across the ridge.  Both are associated with a holloway.

Enclosing_Summary: Low banks running for several metres were observed in 2011 by West Berkshire HER Officer on the northern side of the enclosure running along the contours of a steep slope now in woodland.  A possible ditch survives in the E.  A small excavation showed a ploughed down bank of simple dump construction and a U-shaped ditch.  The ditch had an internal step.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Survive as two parallel banks in N and E. Only the ditch survives as cropmark elsewhere
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Low banks running for several metres were observed in 2011 by West Berkshire HER Officer on the northern side of the enclosure running along the contours of a steep slope now in woodland.  A possible ditch survives in the east.  A small excavation showed a ploughed down bank of simple dump construction and a U-shaped ditch.  The ditch had an internal step.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Where excavated bank was found to be formed from sandy soils and clay with flints.  Possibly unfinished
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: A fragment of ditch in the N-E partially following the 149m contour is recorded on the 1:25,000 1931-61 OS map

Enclosing_Summary: Two banks with medial ditch visible with possible buried outer ditch not determined. Measures 390m by 490m. Bank running into E side of fort possibly boundary earthwork.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Medial ditch visible; possible outer ditch buried, but not determined.

Enclosing_Summary: Univallate and semi-circular comprising a single bank which survives to a maximum height of 1m, earth and dry-stone wall, and a ditch between 4-6m wide in places. A counterscarp bank up to 4m wide and 1m high constructed from material quarried from the ditch lies outside the main defences.  The ditch was originally 2m deeper
Enclosing_Quadrant_Comments: Curving single bank and ditch and counterscarp in the south

Enclosing_Summary: A nearly circular ditch between two banks; the outer bank possibly a counterscarp. The defences around the southern and western sides of the site have been largely ploughed out.  On the northern side the defences consist of a bank, ditch, and possible counterscarp.  Gray (1839) reported that a farmer had dug up several loads of great sarsen stones that had been laid regularly over a layer of flints. Augering had indicated that similar stones may have been present along part of the bank. Gray also reported that some sarsens from the site were broken up and used to repair roads. Possible gang working.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Wood & Hardy (1962:55) noted the presence of a large sarsen stone near the south west perimeter and speculated that the ramparts, might have been faced with sarsens.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: A nearly circular ditch between two banks; the outer bank may be a counterscarp.The defences around the southern and western sides of the site have been largely ploughed out.  On the northern side the defences consist of a bank, ditch, and possible counterscarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Magnetic signals from the area of the bank and the fill of the ditch were high suggesting the presence of a considerable quantity of burnt material.
