Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible berms evident and counterscarp traces. Bank of chalk rubble.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavations (Dyer 1976) suggest the following sequence: Period 1 rampart 4th-3rd century BC, of box construction with some of the vertical posts being replaced at least twice, possible horizontal tie beams, a footing trench for outer facing timbers, chalk and turf packing within the box. The ditch was flat-bottomed, 3m deep, 6.7m wide at the top and 2m at the bottom. In places a berm separated the rampart and ditch. Period 3 rebuilding may be 1st century BC (Belgic?) and saw the recutting of the ditch, V-shaped 6.1m wide and 2.4m deep and the piling up of chalk rubble over the decaying Period 1 rampart to form a dump rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: Univallate with a ditch comprising of two conjoining enclosures W and E. Part of W rampart still surviving to 1,5m high but elsewhere identified as crop mark. In 1933 limited excavations across the S ramparts uncovered the bases of the bank which measured up to 8m in width and contained evidence of timber frameworks and revetment, probably two phases. The first, a narrow palisade with traces of an incomplete bank, is now thought to date from the Late Bronze Age (c.1,000 to 700 BC), in the Middle Iron Age (c.400 BC), more substantial banks were constructed on the earlier alignments and accompanied by large external ditches some 8m across and 2.7m in depth. Evidence of burning and collapse suggests that the later banks were relatively short lived,

A main bank with ditch and counterscarp bank for much of the N and SW circuit, single bank only on the NW and on the E where the outer line has been destroyed. The inner bank varies between 3.0 and 4.5m high, the counterscarp on the W is 2m high and the remaining scarp on the E is 2.0m high. Excavation and geophysics on the E showed two ditches, no excavation of the rampart (Stansbie et. al. 2012). The distance between the main bank and counterscarp is 20m in places.

Main_Display_Name: Prae Wood, Hertfordshire (St. Albans; Verulamium; Verlamion)
Enclosing_Summary: N/A as not a hillfort
N/A as not a hillfort
N/A as not a hillfort

A univallate sub-rectangular enclosure of c.2ha, measures overall 220.0m NE-SW by 130.0m transversely and comprises a weak ditch averaging 4.0m wide and 0.5m deep, with traces of an inner bank, 4.0m wide and less than 0.2m high, destroyed at the NE
Nil
No details recorded. Faint traces of a hollow traversing the neck are visible on satellite imagery (SH)
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possible ditch visible on satellite imagery

Enclosing_Summary: No details recorded and nothing visible on satellite imagery
Headland is cut off from the mainland by a single earthen bank running NE and SW for c. 55m. It is likely to be an agricultural enclosure (SH)
Two ditches, probably with upcast ramparts.
Single rampart around part of the summit
The peninsula is cut off near 'Duveel Point' by a straight earthen bank running ENE and WSW for c. 162m; it has the appearance of an old field fence on satellite imagery (SH).

Main_Display_Name: Castlethorn, West Lothian (Canniewell Slack; Torphichen Hills; Torphichen)
Enclosing_Summary: Two eccentric walls, of which the outer is treated here as the fort
None known
No details recorded. Only feature visible on satellite imagery is what is almost certainly a field fence cutting across the promontory on the E

The promontory fort comprises of a small headland cut off by a low bank with a partially back-filled external ditch. The bank consisted of the upcast from the ditch and the dark crumbly occupation layer, having a height of approximately 1.5m. It showed no indication of having been revetted or of having held a palisade. The ditch is 5m wide with sloping sides and a maximum depth of 2.4m. There was no evidence of re-cutting. Two sherds of Bii amphora were recovered from the middle fill of the ditch while a child burial was found in the upper layers along with medieval pottery.
Single rampart with a second at one end

Main_Display_Name: Moor Dam, Fife (Trench Knowe; Keir Wood)
Enclosing_Summary: Two ramparts and ditches, accompanied by an outer counterscarp bank

No details of any defences are available, and the only feature visible on satellite imagery is a cleft some 5m broad in the bogland surface at the root of the promontory on the landward side of the neck; it is not clear whether this is natural or artificial (SH).
No details of any defences are available
No details of any defences are available, and none are visible on satellite imagery (SH).
No details of any defences are available and none are visible on satellite imagery (SH)
A possible bank with an external ditch about 5m wide cuts off the approach to the promontory from the NE
No details of any defences are available, but satelite imagery shows a possible bank enclosing the E tip

Egg-shaped enclosure measuring 112m W-E by 18m N-S enclosing 0.62ha. It comprises at least three, possibly four narrow concentric palisade trenches approximately 5m and 2m apart from inner to outer rampart. In the N, a 2m wide ditch leaves the main path of the palisade trench and follows the palisade, terminating at the entrance.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Possibly a fourth palisade trench, but unconfirmed.  The palisades were probably not all contemporary
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: At least three narrow concentric palisade trenches
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Palisade trenches and a broader ditch

Enclosing_Summary: Approximately 90m NE-SW by 80m transversely enclosing 0.4ha. Comprising a bank 0.5m high spread to a width of approximately 14m and a broad ditch approximately 0.8m deep. A possible palisade trench runs concentric to the ditch at a distance of approximately 10m, with traces of a slight bank between.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly earlier phase as suggested by palisade trench

Enclosing_Summary: Two possible banks drawn in an arc across the approach from the NE are visible on satellite imagery
First identified from aerial photographs by Casey (1999, 198), fieldwork indicates there are no defences here.
Linear erosion features are visible cutting across the broad neck of this promontory at the head of the high coastal cliffs
Fort comprises a rampart and ditch drawn across the neck

A linear feature is visible on satellite imagery midway along the broader end of the island some 150m N of the S end, though it is not clear whether this is the remains of a boundary wall, or perhaps a geological feature visible in the exposed rock of the cliff on the W (SH).
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: A boundary wall or a geological feature

Enclosing_Summary: Ruin of a possible wall cutting across the neck on the E is visible on satellite imagery.
Simple minor bank and ditch cuts across the neck of the promontory. Neither the bank nor the ditch is more than 1.5m wide.
The only feature visible here on satellite imagery is an old field fence cutting across the landward side of a series of minor promontories along the cliff-edge
There are no recorded banks, ditches or walls.
No information is available about any defences, and none are visible on satellite imagery.
Sub-circular enclosure formed from a single narrow ditch or trench for a palisade. It measures in the region of 65m N-S by 60m E-W enclosing 0.25ha.
Two almost circular concentric ditches 5-10m wide measuring approximately 75m by 80m and 100m by 110m with a 8-12m separation.  The inner ditch encloses approximately 0.33ha.
No detailed information about any defences available, and no evidence of any on satellite imagery.
Three banks are noted crossing the neck, but no detailed information is available
A ditch no more than 1.5m broad can be seen cutting across the neck on satellite imagery.

There is no detailed information available about any defences, which have probably been identified from aerial photographs, but as a result of the misinterpretation of natural features, and there is no evidence of any enclosing works on any satellite imagery (SH).
There is no evidence of any enclosing works on this inaccessible promontory
Probably fenced with a bank to keep beasts off a treacherous convex slope dropping into the cliff-edge

Surrounded by bank and ditch, latter as slight depression. Levelled on E side, where possible entrance. Possible second bank c. 20m distant from concentric with inner bank on E side. Ploughed down to N and S and built over on E. Concentric field boundary outside this bank possible third line.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Possible second bank c. 20m distant from concentric with inner bank on E side. Ploughed down to N and S and built over on E. Concentric field boundary outside this bank possible third line. Not included in quadrants.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Slight depression to outer of inner bank.

Enclosing_Summary: Most heavily defended on E, with four banks defining site, but two elsewhere. A well-preserved inner rampart completes the circuit to 2m above interior and 3m high above external ditch, covered  with gorse and scrub. The three outer banks on the E and one elsewhere are in various stages of damage and much ploughed, surviving to only c. 0.3m - 0.5m in height under improved pasture.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Probably four on E and two elsewhere.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by earthwork bank, best preserved on S, but much ploughed and only to 0.25m high and almost gone on N side. No evidence of ditches, may be buried.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Bank almost gone on N side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: None visible. Probably buried feature now.

Enclosing_Summary: Single wall across promontory
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Single piece of vitrified stone found

Enclosing_Summary: The only enclosures visible on satellite imagery are likely to be agricultural on the higher ground
The only features cutting across the neck visible on satellite imagery are evidently successive field fences of no great age (SH).

Main_Display_Name: Flimston Bay Camp, Castlemartin, Pembrokeshire (Flimston Castle; Flimston Bay Promontory Fort)
Enclosing_Summary: Good series of three curving banks and ditches, c. 120m in length, cut off the promontory on the N, but the main defence is bivallate. Close-set double bank and ditch to 10m high and 1.1m high ands 10m wide and 1.1m deep respectively, sited to W of central entrance. Two scarps, to 3m high with outer ditch, 12m wide and 2.1m deep, to E of entrance, but disturbed by later quarrying. Third denuded bank, to c.1.4m high and 8m wide, with traces of outer ditch, sited c. 30m to N of the two inner ramparts.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Third denuded bank, to c.1.4m high and 8m wide, with traces of outer ditch, sited c. 30m to N of the two inner ramparts, producing, in effect, an annexe, and/or indication of phased construction.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Third denuded bank, to c. 1.4m high and 8m wide, with traces of outer ditch, sited c. 30m to N of the two inner ramparts, producing, in effect, an annexe, and/or indication of phased construction. Included in quadrants as annexe uncertain.

Main_Display_Name: Crocksydam Camp, Pembrokeshire (Crockeydam Camp; Moody Nose)
Enclosing_Summary: Headland cut of on N by single semicircular bank, to 1m high, and slight ditch, c. 100m long. Grimes (1931) found evidence of stone wall.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Grimes suggests stone walling in bank.

Enclosing_Summary: Double palisade trench filled with stones and varying in depth from a few centimetres to 0.5m and 0.5m wide.  No evidence for the use of timber was recovered and  the trench does not appear to continue in the E so may not have been complete. It was later replaced by three stone ramparts except in the E where there is only a single rampart. The remains today are most visible in the N
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Excavation (Burgess 1971) showed the settlement was originally enclosed by a double palisade which was incomplete in its first phase then replaced and completed with stone ramparts
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Three stone ramparts except in the E where there is only a single rampart.

Main_Display_Name: Buckspool Down Camp, Pembrokeshire (Buckspool Camp; The Castle, Castle Head)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving series of three banks and ditches defend a triangular promontory, the neck of which has been severely cut into on both sides by the sea, the main bank in effect built on a bridge of rock joining the promontory to the mainland. Inner bank and ditch most disturbed by quarrying and partially levelled. Bank c. 30m long and c. 70m above interior. Central bank best, curving for c. 104m and between 15m and 20m from inner bank and 2m over the ditch. Simple gap entrance c. 30m from S end of the bank.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Internal area c. 0.55ha, but erosion makes assessment difficult.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Outer bank appears to define an annexe as runs from the entrance, through inner bank and then NNW. Uncertain and included in quadrants.

Enclosing_Summary: Main defence is 180m of double bank and ditch with simple entrance towards S end. An inner bank, with no ditch, lies 30m inside the promontory, with smaller lateral banks attaching it to the main defences. Inside still are a slighter, and possibly earlier, bank and ditch, probably of a later phase.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Slighter, and possibly earlier, bank and ditch, probably of a later phase, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Inner enclosure defined by two ploughed banks and ditches on its S side, with only one bank and ditch around entire circuit. Rampart of outer horseshoe-shaped enclosure close to S side of inner enclosure, forming, in effect, a multivallate defence for the entire site, but elsewhere it diverges. On W of this outer circuit bank best and to 2m high above ditch bottom, with good counterscarp.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Morphology suggests phased construction, but no details.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches to inner enclosure, one to outer.

Enclosing_Summary: Curving outward facing scarp c. 1.5m high, defines SE and E sides of enclosure. Old silage pit breaches NE end. Traces of outside ditch.

Multivallate, oval in form estimated at 120m N-S by 80m E-W. Up to three concentric ditches set approximately 10m apart within a further ditch separated by 15-20m.  The internal area measures approximately 60m N-S by 50m E-W.

Large inner bank and ditch and smaller outer bank on the gentler N side. On the steep SE and SW there is a slight bank with terracing below to create the illusion of massive works. Palisades are a feature.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Palisades determined as feature of site.

Enclosing_Summary: On approachable N side c. 45m long bank cuts off the spur, to 2m high with outer rock-cut ditch c. 5m wide. Surveyed  by Mytum and Webster (2001), who noted two lines of stones of possible palisade surmounting bank.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Two lines of stones of possible palisade surmounting bank.

Enclosing_Summary: About 46m rampart and ditch cuts of the promontory on approachable NE side to give internal area c. 36m deep. Bank c. 2m high and ditch 5m wide.

Natural defence on E, S and W, with double bank and ditch, c. 80m long, cutting off the promontory on the approachable N side. Inner rampart to 3m high internally and 5m above the ditch, the outer bank to 2m high internally and 1.3m externally, with no ditch visible. It is possible that this outer bank is in fact a counterscarp rather than a separate rampart, as suggested by Avent in 1981.

An inner bank rises to 2m above a wide shallow ditch, with the outer bank to over 3m exterior and dominating the inner bank in places. Outer ditch nearly ploughed out.  Field bank runs along outer bank's crest. Interior divided into two fields by curving rampart NE-S to 2m high on W, with shallow ditch.
Crescentic double banks and rock-cut ditches 80m long cuts off the spur on NE.

Main_Display_Name: Foel Drygarn, Pembrokeshire (Moel Drygarn; Moel Trigarn; Foel Trigarn; Foel Drycarn; Foeltrigarn)
Enclosing_Summary: Circuit comprises two widely-spaced, now dilapidated and vegetation covered, stone/earth banks, with traces of flanking ditches. Inner bank rises c. 1m above interior and c. 3m-4m above ditch, into which it has largely collapsed, masking its outline. Outer bank less, with dry-stone wall facing visible on inner and outer face, as well as on outer face of inner bank. Set against natural cliffs on S side, where no built defence. Outer bank meets inner on W side.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Overall three possible enclosures, of which innermost, on the summit, probably earliest.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Set against natural slopes on S side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Ramparts now part dry-stone and part-earth with stone revetment. Originally probably stone walls.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Faint traces of ditch to main enclosure.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by simple dry-stone wall, with no evident ditch, incorporating rock outcrops and fronting onto precipitous slopes of Carn Alw on E.  Some facework still visible, but now mostly collapsed stone.

Protected by steep natural slopes on N, E and W with very spread bank and ditch c. 50m long E-W cutting off the promontory to SW, and making use of natural gully at E end. Possible outer ditch, c. 40m outside, and SW, of the main bank and ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possible outer ditch, c. 40m outside, and SW, of the main bank and ditch.

Enclosing_Summary: Straight bank and ditch, c. 40m long, cuts off the promontory on E. Bank to  2.8m high above the ditch. Ditch c. 3m wide with counterscarp
Low bank, formerly to c. 0.3m high, cutting off spur promontory on NW, now levelled and planted with avenue of trees to Fynone House.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Tre Ruffydd, Pembrokeshire (Castelltreruffydd; Castell Tre-Riffith; Castell Treuffydd)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving 90m bank of earth and stone and traces of ditch cutting off a NE-facing narrow isthmus on the SW in 1925. Now all but lost.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: No evidence now, but probably stone-wall.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of ditch in 1925 - now gone.

Main_Display_Name: Glandwr Isaf Camp, Pembrokeshire (Glan-Dwr-Isaf Camp; Castell Joan; Castell Moylgrove)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by natural scarps except on ENE where bank and ditch cross the approachable side.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Felinganol, Pembrokeshire (Castellfelinganol; Castell Felin-Ganol; Castellfelorganol)
Enclosing_Summary: Single, revetted, rampart c. 110m long and to 5m high above an outer rock-cut ditch cutting off the promontory on NNE.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Revetted externally and internally by vertically-pitched slates, thought by RCAHMW not to be original.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Pen-yr-Allt, Llantood, Pembrokeshire (Castell Pen yr Allt)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving rampart cuts of  promontory on N quadrants, standing to 7m above rock-cut ditch c. 5m-6m wide. No bank on W side and no main bank to S, although ditch and counterscarp in evidence.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Interior area not defined, but around 0.3ha.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Probable earth and stone bank originally. Counterscarp to S.

Enclosing_Summary: Irregular oval measuring 132m by 90m with at least two banks and two ditches.
Ordnance Survey in 1966 recorded widely-spaced double ramparts across the base of the promontory on N and a single rampart cutting off the tip of the apex on S. No evidence for ditches.

Main_Display_Name: y Castell, Bridell, Pembrokeshire (Castell; Cwmbettws Defended Enclosure, Bridell)
Enclosing_Summary: Natural protection on N, S and SW, with curving bank and ditch cutting off the spur to S and SE. The

Defined by steep natural slopes on SE to NW sides, with bank, c. 47m long and to 1.2m high, cutting off the promontory on easily approachable NE side.  Bank 1.7m high recorded by Ordnance Survey 1974. Ditch not recorded, possibly buried feature.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch not recorded, possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Single bank and ditch defends N and W, bank to 2.8m externally. Discontinuous on N and petering out.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Good ditch on NW, but follows lane on N.

Enclosing_Summary: Oval in form, imeasuring 151m NE-SW by 91m transversely. It survives only in the N as the remains of an ill-defined scarp 1.3m high and traces of a ditch. Satellite imagery suggest two banks in the NE but this is uncertain.

Main_Display_Name: South Buckton Moor, Northumberland (Buckton Moor South Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Sub-circular in plan it comprises a scarped platform enclosed by a earthen bank 15m wide and 1.5m high and an outer ditch.  The internal area, measured from satellite imagery is approximately 0.4ha and the whole site footprint 1.1ha. Traces of a possible inner bank.

hree massive banks running E-W for c. 45m  and ditches cut off the promontory on the W side, elsewhere protected by the steep slopes. Inner bank to 5m above interior and 4m above ditch. Middle bank rises to 3.2m high and outer 2m high. No outside ditch visible.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No outer ditch visible - possibly buried feature.

Main_Display_Name: Posty Draw, Bletherston, Pembrokeshire (Post y Draw)
Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart,65m long and to 2m high, and filled-in ditch cutting off the promontory on N. At W end rampart stops 5m short of the steep drop. Earth and clay construction of bank.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and clay construction of bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch filled in and now mere undulations.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Rhyd-y-Brwyn, Pembrokeshire (Castell Cymmer; Rhyd-y-Brwyn; Rhyd-Brown Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Complex arrangement of slight bank on all sides, becoming higher on N and NW and supplemented by a ditch and two massive outer banks and ditch, which rise to 5m above the ditches. and running for 170m+ and 70m wide.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Fort shows evidence of remodelling, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Single dry-stone rampart surviving to circa 3m and in places incorporates three natural rock outcrops, now collapsed and spread; best on the N side. Possibly no ditch existed.

Main_Display_Name: Tyganol Fort, Nevern, Pembrokeshire (Tycanol Fort; Ty Canol; Ty-Canol; Tycanol Wood)
Enclosing_Summary: Promontory cut off on SSW by stone and earth wall and ditch.

Ovoid in plan comprising a single rampart measuring 64m N-S by 40m E-W enclosing 0.2ha. Turf-covered earth and stone bank measuring 6m wide now stands up to 0.5m high. Northumberland HER also refer to an internal ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Recorded by Northumberland HER but not by EH field investigators.  Possibly the 'robber trench' identified during a Hillfort Atlas Project visit

Enclosing_Summary: Much rock and scree with interior sectioned out into series of enclosures by walls linking from outcrop to outcrop, but some facework survives. Walls visible on N, E and W. Cross-walls suggest four sections and possibly phases of construction, with the first around the N summit. No evidence for ditches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Cross-walls suggest four sections and possibly phases of construction, with the first around the N summit.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Multiple interior walls, but only outside rampart recorded.

Enclosing_Summary: To E and S land rises gently, and here defended by single curving bank and ditch c. 80m long, bank rising to 1.3m above ditch. Ditch regularly ploughed and now hollow and E end virtually gone likewise.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch regularly ploughed and now hollow.

Main_Display_Name: Castell-y-Fuwch, Pembrokeshire (Castle Fuwch; Parc Castell; Castell y Bwch; Cas-Fuwch; Castell-y-Cwch)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank and ditch with intermittent counterscarp. Bank c. 2.7m above ditch and 1m above interior. Bank less on S and ditch best on N and W.

Two well-preserved curving ramparts, c. 100m long, cut off the promontory on W and NW. Inner higher to 1.6m above interior and to 5m above ditch, whilst outer bank rises to 3.2m above ditch. This whole system some 25m wide in good order except outer ditch affected and destroyed by ploughing in places.
Defined by single bank and ditch to S, bank rising to 2m above ditch, but only 0.4m above interior. Rubble on S may be relict stone wall
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Rubble on S may be relict stone wall.

Enclosing_Summary: Oval in plan, it measures 122m NW-SE by 112m transversely and comprised two wide concentric banks with a medial ditch and a further narrow outer ditch. On the inside traces of a possible palisade trench or slot for a box rampart have been recorded.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: A third inner ditch, possibly for a box rampart or a palisade suggests more than one phase
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone recorded but it is uncertain if the bank was faced

Enclosing_Summary: NA

Bivallate and approximately oval in plan the inner rampart measures 47.5m E-W by 61.5m N-S enclosing 0.21ha. It comprises a single earth and stone rampart of between 5-9m wide and standing up to 3m high.  In the W separated from the inner rampart by approximately 60m is a further outer circuit 5m wide and up to 1.5m high. Beyond this is a ditch 3m wide and 0.5m deep. The two ramparts are joined together by a short section of bank which runs NE-SW
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly multi-period. RCHME field investigation in 1955 reports a further inner bank, with the enclosure later extended. Settlement within and between the enclosing banks would qualify this as a multiple enclosure fort, although the settlement is probably not contemporary with the hillfort

Enclosing_Summary: Oval in plan approximately 85m by 90m, comprising two banks and an outer ditch. The inner bank survives poorly and only measurable in the N where it is approximately 4m wide and 0.4m high.  The rest of the circuit can be made out by the presence of a few stones protruding from the turf and it probably coincided with the top of a rocky escarpment in the W.  The outer stone bank measures 3-5m wide and 0.3-1.4m high and is stronger in the W where it runs to the foot of the escarpment. The outer ditch has an average width of 8m and depth of 0.7.

Oval earthwork measuring approximately 100m NW-SW by 70m SW-NE with two concentric earth and stone banks.  In 1955 the inner and best preserved bank varied between 4-5 in width and up to 0.5m high. The outer bank is only visible in the W and N and measures 3-4, wide and up to 0.4m high.  Further faint traces of this bank can be seen in the E.
Circular enclosure 100m in diameter.
Between five and eight concentric ditches including two sets of double palisades separated by 3m

Main_Display_Name: Castell Cynon, Pembrokeshire (Tre-Gynon Fort; Tre-Gynon Camp; Tregynon)
Enclosing_Summary: Protected by the steep slopes on E and by single, substantial, curving rampart and ditch on W, rampart rising to  4m above exterior and to 2.8m above interior.

Defined by earth and shaly-stone bank and ditch set back from the break of slope, best on N where bank rises to 3m over shallow ditch 5m wide and 0.5m deep. Hedge bank on W where defences run parallel to it where bank to 1m high with traces of ditch. S and E sides now defined by scarp slopes.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and shaly-stone bank construction visible.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Trefach, Nevern, Pembrokeshire (Castell Tre-Fach; Tre-Fach Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart, 3.3m above exterior and 2.8m above interior, with filled-in ditch cuts off the promontory on approachable N side.
On gentle to flat to N and NE side three massive banks and ditches, at highest top of rampart 7.5m above ditch bottom. Possible silted ditch E-W across interior.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possible silted ditch E-W across interior.

Main_Display_Name: Clawdd y Milwyr, Pembrokeshire (St David's Head Camp; Warrior's Dyke)
Enclosing_Summary: Massive inner spread-rubble former stone wall and outer ditch runs for c. 100m, with bare stone exposed on E, with maximum of 3m high from base of ditch and c.10m wide. Ditch c. 4m wide and 0.5m deep. Wall-faces of three to four courses of dry-stone masonry visible towards the N end of exterior. Two slighter walls with ditches lie outside this main defence. Inner is of earth stone bank, to 1m high and 4m wide with no ditch, and may be a counterscarp or some other component of the defences. Third bank lies 4m -5m from it.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Morphology indicates possible phased construction, but no details.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Two slighter walls with ditches lie outside main defence. Inner is of earth stone bank, to 1m high and 4m wide with no ditch, and may be a counterscarp or some other component of the defences.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site. Two slighter walls with ditches lie outside main defence. Inner is of earth stone bank, to 1m high and 4m wide with no ditch, and may be a counterscarp or some other component of the defences.

Enclosing_Summary: Promontory cut off at neck on SW by c. 68m of bank and ditch, former rising to 2.3m above latter, with low counterscarp bank.

Defined by single bank and well-defined ditch, to 4m high, with additional outer bank and good ditch to 1.8m in height on gentler, and approachable, W. On precipitous E the rock outcrop is incorporated into the bank. Site probably stone-walled and possible crude walling has been reported, but no details.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Site probably stone-walled and possible crude walling has been reported, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Formed by two closely-set ditches which measure 155m NE-SW by 140m transversely across the outer ditch, and approximately 105m NW-SE across the inner ditch.

Defined by fragments of bivallate bank and ditch, but difficult to quantify because of gorse on site. No defences on W and NW, elsewhere fragments of  widely-spaced banks, inner poorly defined, but both best on S, where inner just visible on aerial photographs and outer to 1m high.

Main_Display_Name: Hazel Grove Camp South, Pembrokeshire (Little Treffgarne Wood Enclosure)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving rampart and ditch cuts of N and E, but also runs on crest of steep slope on S. Bank to 3.2m above the ditch to 2m deep. Curving bank divides interior of uncertain origin.

Main_Display_Name: Garn Fechan, Llanwnda, Pembrokeshire (Gaer Fach; y Gaer Vychan)
Enclosing_Summary: Single tumbled stone rampart protects site, rising to 0.7m above interior and 2.6m above exterior.  Best beneath crags on E. Ramparts elsewhere, slighter and vegetation covered making interpretation difficult. No ditch visible.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Rampart best beneath crags on E. Elsewhere, slighter and vegetation covered making interpretation difficult.

Main_Display_Name: Parc Castell, Pont Cwm-Bach, Pembrokeshire (Old Castle Plantation)
Enclosing_Summary: Defended on N, W and SW sides by discontinuous spread bank and shallow ditch. Elsewhere natural scarps, possibly steepened, form defence. Possible counterscarp. Possibly unfinished.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possibly earth and stone bank. Possible counterscarp. Possibly unfinished.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Pant-y-Phillip, Pembrokeshire (Parc y Castell; Castell)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank and ditch to E and S and seemingly scarping of natural slopes to N and W, where bank virtually gone on ground but visible as parch marks on aerial photographs. Best preserved on S where bank to 1m high above interior and to 2.3m external and good ditch. Possible

Main_Display_Name: Tower Point, St. Brides, Pembrokeshire (Tower Point Rath)
Enclosing_Summary: Two banks and ditches with counterscarp, c. 140m long, cut off the promontory on E. Inner bank 14.5m wide and 3m high with ditch. Slight central bank and ditch and then counterscarp 9m wide and 0.8m high. Excavations showed the inner bank of two phases: first of clay faced with stone, second phase more stony bank revetted with stepped walls, a murus duplex.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Excavations in 1970 showed the inner bank of two phases, first of clay faced with stone, second phase more stony bank revetted with stepped walls, a murus duplex. No details of whether initial single bank.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavations showed the inner bank of two phases: first of clay faced with stone, second phase more stony bank revetted with stepped walls, a murus duplex.

Enclosing_Summary: Stony rampart and ditch cutting across promontory neck, former to 2m-2.5m above latter. Bank continues around promontory on E and W for c. 25m-30m before fading out.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stony construction of rampart revealed in eroded section on N.

Enclosing_Summary: An earthen bank measuring 1.4m in width and 0.6m in height runs E-W across the headland. This bank is stone-faced.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Depression noted at the foot of the bank on the N

Main_Display_Name: Clegyr Boia, Pembrokeshire (Clegyr-Boia; Clegyr Voia; Clegyr-Foia)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by rampart rising 0.6m and to 4.6m wide above interior and using natural outcrops in its circuit. Rampart composed of stone rubble and earth revetted with stone blocks. No ditch.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site. Rampart composed of stone rubble and earth.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Rampart composed of stone rubble and earth revetted with stone blocks.

Enclosing_Summary: Westropp (1921, 109-110) describes 'curved fosse' to N and W through which a lane ran to the rocky shore below. Ditch is now eroded on the W side but extant to the N, though it has been cut back into the interior; the landward side is stone-faced.

Westropp (1914, 100) describes two earthen banks with an intermediate ditch traversing the neck on the N from E to W over a distance of c. 14m. the outer bank measures 5m in width while the inner bank measures c. 3m in width. The intervening ditch is c. 7m wide. No other information available

Main_Display_Name: Castell Heinif, Pembrokeshire (Castell Meinif; Castell Henif; Castell Menif)
Enclosing_Summary: Landward side on E protected by curving bivallate rampart, c. 115m long, with inner bank to 2.5m above interior and 2.3m above bottom of ditch. Outer bank similar. On SE, an additional long, but slight, curving bank located between the main two, its purpose unclear, but possible to protect an entrancehere, or could be later. Banks composed of earth and stone with dry-stone revetment revealed in erosion pockets, now repaired.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Banks composed of earth and stone with dry-stone revetment revealed in erosion pockets, now repaired.

Enclosing_Summary: Three curving inner banks close-set and parallel,c. 120m long, with inner bank to 4m above ditch, second and third less substantial at 1m-2m above ditches. Outer bank c. 20m lower than inner because of slope and is straighter, possibly showing phased construction. Second and third banks stop short of cliff edge and probably lost to sea.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Outer bank c. 20m lower than inner because of slope and is straighter, possibly showing phased construction, but no details.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Penpleidiau, Pembrokeshire (Caerfai Camp; Penpleidiau Camp; Pen Pleiddiau)
Enclosing_Summary: Three to four rubble banks and ditches cut off the promontory on N for c. 100m.

Four or five banks and ditch. Outer bank on E most massive, with no outer ditch, but to c. 4m wide and over 3m above a rock-cut ditch on its inner W side. Second bank to W consists of unexcavated bedrock between two ditches, rather than built bank. Two more sets of slight bank and ditch to W then gap of 20m. Here promontory widens out and protected by a further bank running along a natural rise.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible rubble bank using natural bedrock along line.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Coch, Tremynydd, Pembrokeshire (Castell Coch, Aberdinas)
Enclosing_Summary: Two curving banks with ditch cross the neck of the promontory on E for c. 70m from each cliff top to N and S. Inner bank to over 2m above ditch to S of entrance Outer bank has berm and is less. Both banks slighter to N. Three lines of rampart S of entrance were recorded by Ordnance Survey 1966.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Three lines of rampart S of entrance were recorded by Ordnance Survey 1966.

Enclosing_Summary: No details of any defences are available

Narrower neck on the NE defended by five earthen banks with up to four intermediate ditches. Bank one (int. H 1.6m) and bank two are substantial; bank three is low (H 0.7m); bank four and five are similar to bank three, but only extend southwards from the entrance, a distance of 84m. Bank two stone-faced externally; less substantial from entrance to N side. The line has evidently been re-used for the line of agricultural boundaries
A ditch extends across the neck of the promontory from N to S over a distance of c. 15m. It is c. 1.5m in width and 0.3m in depth.
It is defended to the W by an earthen bank and ditch which extends across the neck from N to S over a distance of c. 20m.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The addition of Minane Island creates a significantly larger enclosure

Main_Display_Name: Caer Aber Pwll, Caerau, Pembrokeshire (Caerau, Aber-Pwll)
Enclosing_Summary: Enclosed by series of up to four banks and ditches extending to 172m in width.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly result of two periods of construction, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Promontory cut off by 1m high bank incorporating a 2.5m high natural mound within it. No ditch defined. To NW part of the steep slope possibly scarped with traces of bank and ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch defined to SW bank. Possible trace of ditch on NW, but uncertain.

Main_Display_Name: Gribin Promontory Fort, Solva, Pembrokeshire (Solva Head; Gribyn)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by spread stony bank, probably remains of stone-wall, on N and S sides above the steep slopes to 0.5m above interior, with no ditch. On NE stony bank to 1m high and 6m wide with rock-cut ditch to 1.5m deep and 4m wide. At SW corner c. 15m bank to 2m high and 6m wide with external ditch 5m wide and 0.5m deep. Low stony bank on W side.
Irregular in form, approximately 0.2ha with a single rampart to the N and E terminating at either end of the cliff edge. No evidence of ditches.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Assumed to be an earthen bank as no sign of stonework on satelite imagery

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by single bank, to 4m wide and 0.5m high internally, with ditch to 6m wide and 2m deep cutting off the 25m wide promontory neck on N.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Coastal erosion, sea stacks off seaward end

Enclosing_Summary: It is connected to the mainland via a narrow eroding neck of land (Wth 3m; L 15m) across which are the remains of three earthen banks (max. Wth 3m; max. H 0.65m) and shallow ditches (max. Wth 2m).

Main_Display_Name: Simonside Camp, Northumberland (Weetwood Camp, Weetwood Moor)
Enclosing_Summary: Oval in form, enclosing 1.2ha, ramparts difficult to discern, but two ditches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Areas estimated. It is clear that there are enclosures overlying the main defences of the fort
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: It has the appearance of two ditches on GE satellite imagery 2006

Enclosing_Summary: Circular enclosure 63m in diameter enclosing 0.24ha. Two earth and stone banks and an outer ditch.  The main rampart averages 8m wide and up to 1.3m high, separated from a further rampart by 5m. The second rampart is 5m wide and up to 1m high and best preserved on the N, W and SE sides.  The outer ditch is 3m wide and 0.4m deep with a counterscarp bank in the SW quadrant.  Elsewhere the ditch in infilled and the bank levelled.

6th century BC palisaded enclosure of three concentric oak palisades (Jobey 1968). Overlying this an oval enclosure 94m NE-SW by 72m transversely enclosed by two stone-faced ramparts, the inner measuring 4m wide and 0.8m high, the outer, separated from the inner rampart by 10m, visible only on the S and E sides. Outside the ramparts a shallow depression represents the remains of a ditch.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Inner rampart only visible in the S and E

Main_Display_Name: Porth y Bwch, Pembrokeshire (Pen Dinas Fach)
Enclosing_Summary: Defences vitually gone consisting of only a 2m stretch of low bank, c. 0.3m, high cutting off landward neck of promontory on NE. Possible slight trace of ditch.

Defences best on SW beneath a hedge-bank where single earth bank with no trace of ditch rises to c. 2m externally. On N and S only a scarp to c. 1.5m high externally at W end, but fading to nil at E. At NE, spread bank to 6m wide and 0.5m high, fading to nothing at SE corner. Traces of ditch at NE corner.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Quadrants estimated, as defences light and difficult to interpret.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of ditch at NE corner.

Enclosing_Summary: Three substantial banks and ditches cut off the promontory on NW for c. 110m across and 50m wide; elsewhere defended by the steep slopes. Substantial inner earth and stone bank, rising to over 3m high, and rock-cut ditch, largest of three. Middle bank to 1.5m high, with shallow ditch, whlist outer to 1.3m high with no ditch visible.Other two outer banks not concentric with inner and gap of c. 17m between outer edge of inner ditch and middle bank, suggesting two phased construction. At S end, space of c. 12m between middle and outer banks.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Other two outer banks not concentric with inner and gap of c. 17m between outer edge of inner ditch and middle bank, suggesting two phased construction, but no details.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Inner rock-cut, middle bank ditch shallow and outer bank ditch not visible.

Enclosing_Summary: Two lines of bank and ditch, formerly stone-walls, cut off the promontory at its narrow neck on NE, with the high sea cliffs on the other sides. Inner, c. 45m long, stands to 3m above base of ditch and 1.7m above interior, whilst outer sited c. 25m NE of inner.

Inner central walled area, c. 110m by 85m, of c. 0.7ha,with 1m-2m high rampart with no ditch, incorporating four natural outcrops. Two outer ramparts at E end in crags, and another on W encloses an annexe. Linking walling on N and S to E and W walls. Outermost wall on E reinforced by 4m high revetted bank with ditch and counterscarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site. Outermost wall on E reinforced by 4m high revetted bank with ditch and counterscarp.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outermost wall on E reinforced by 4m high revetted bank with ditch and counterscarp.

Enclosing_Summary: Single bank, to 1.5m high, and ditch, to 4.5m wide, c. 30m long, cutting off the promontory on E. A N-S field boundary c. 16m outside this line, may indicate further outer rampart, but no direct evidence for this.

Rampart of earth and stones with ditch cuts off the promontory on E for c. three-quarters across for c. 20m, bank 4m across and to c. 0.6m high. Bank spread at N end. This ends well short of the cliff edge on the S, suggesting site possibly unfinished. RCAHMW (Coflein) suggest from aerial photographs that there are three lines of defence. Outer and middle banks set parallel and cut across promontory at right angles to the cliff. Inner rampart at a diagonal, with possible ditch or quarry pits placed on inner edge; possibly phased construction.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Inner rampart at a diagonal, with possible ditch or quarry pits placed on inner edge; possibly phased construction suggested by RCAHMW (Coflein), but not proven.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: RCAHMW (Coflein) suggest from aerial photographs that there are three lines of defence. Outer and middle banks set parallel and cut across promontory at right angles to the cliff. Inner rampart at a diagonal, with possible ditch or quarry pits placed on inner edge.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone rampart. Bank spread at N end. This ends well short of the cliff edge on the S, suggesting site possibly unfinished.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Definite one, but actual number not defined if three lines of rampart.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Coch, Trevine, Pembrokeshire (Castell Coch, Trefin; Castell Coch, Tref-Fin)
Enclosing_Summary: Two lines of earth and stone rampart cut across the narrow neck of the promontory on ENE, c. 50m-60m wide, outer bank larger, to c. 1m high, with an outer, c. square-cut, rock-cut ditch to 4m wide and 2m deep. Inner bank slightly less, with a slight ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Coch, Penmorfa, Pembrokeshire (Castell-Coch, Penmorfa; Castell Coch, Pen Morfa)
Enclosing_Summary: Two widely-spaced stone ramparts and ditch, c. 25m apart, cut off the promontory on S. Inner bank rises to c. 1.7m above interior and, less substantial, outer bank revetted by modern wall.

At top of island is roughly level earthwork enclosure c. 30m square, with S and W sides defined by low L-plan bank measuring c. 30m E-W by 25m N-S with natural scarps to N and E, possible stone walling.
Protected on S side by low widely-spaced curving banks. Inner greater to 1.2m high with ditch. Entrance

Main_Display_Name: South Castle, Skomer, Pembrokeshire (The Neck Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: The promontory cut off on NE by 100m of single bank and outer ditch with low counterscarp, standing to 4m above base of ditch.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Low counterscarp bank. Probable stone wall.

Main_Display_Name: Marloes Sound Rath, Pembrokeshire (Marloes Rath; Marloes; Gateholm Sound Rath; Watery Bay Rath)
Enclosing_Summary: Three, or possibly four, non-continuous, outer banks with outer ditch, and an inner bank and ditch define the fort. Inner bank curved, running for c. 85m, standing 5m above external ditch, ending at cliff edge at each end. SE entrance, with continuing bank protection to 0.7m high along the cliff edge to the S. Outer ramparts more complex, but less high and rising to c. 3m above the ditch, with two main lines of bank and ditch, with hint of third in between. These diverge towards the W, indicating another phase perhaps. Probably stone walls. Small stream to E of entrance, and on its E side large bank, c. 30m long and o 2m high, with traces of a mostly in-filled ditch on E side provides additional protection for the entrance.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Two-phased, but unclear, construction as inner rampart sufficiently distinct from outer ramparts to indicate separate phase and outer banks diverge to W, indicating perhaps another phase.

Enclosing_Summary: Earthen rampart with periodic ditch, c. 268m long, cuts across lip of N-S valley that separates the promontory plateau from landward. This merges with natural slopes to N.
Double system of banks and ditches with counterscarp cutting off E side of promontory. Defences finished with stone walls and timber work.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: At least three phases of construction confirmed. Possible initial single bank?
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Defences finished with stone walls and timber work.

Enclosing_Summary: Curving bank of stone and rubble and ditch for c. 75m cut off the promontory on N and E, giving blunt interior c. 40m by 50m. Bank rises to 1.5m above the 3m wide ditch. Bank fades at S end.

Main_Display_Name: Little Castle Head, St Ishmael's, Pembrokeshire
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by a single bank cutting across the narrow neck of the promontory to N. Bank rises to 3.7m above external rock-cut ditch to 1.2m deep, probable stone wall. Possible inner ditch, but uncertain.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Rock-cut outer ditch. Possible inner ditch, but uncertain.

Main_Display_Name: South Hook Camp, Pembrokeshire (Kilroom; Rath Park)
Enclosing_Summary: Curvilinear rampart, probable stone wall, and ditch, c. 115m long, cut off the tapering promontory on N and E, from each cliff edge.

The promontory, c. 316m in depth, cut off by two ramparts with medial ditch for c. 68m. Firstly late Bronze Age timber palisades and stone revetted bank followed by Iron Age bank with internal stonework. Outside bank was a deep ditch.  Stone revetment uncovered and still visible.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Excavations to c. 1975 on entrance area found complex phases of development.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone revetment uncovered and still visible.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Firstly late Bronze Age timber palisades and stone revetted bank followed by Iron Age bank with internal stonework. Stone revetment uncovered and still visible.

Main_Display_Name: Great Castle Head, St Ishmael's, Pembrokeshire
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by line of two ramparts, probably stone-walled, c. 150m long, with medial ditch cutting off the mainland on N.

Curvilinear double bank and ditch cuts off the promontory for 145m on the NW with natural scarps elsewhere. Inner bank stands 2m above ditch and outer bank 5m above ditch. Possible revetment on inner bank.

Bank and ditch cut off the narrowest neck of the promontory on the NE running 75m from cliff edge to enclose the first area as an irregular area c. 80m N-S by 40m E-W. Bank stands at c. 2.8m above the ditch. Possible second line of defence along gully where traces of mortared stone wall.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Probably stone-walled site. Traces of mortared stone wall along gully possibly medieval?

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by curving rampart, probably stone-walled, and ditch 105m long cutting off the headland on NE, bank rising to 3m above the ditch and 1.3m high internally. Ditch rock-cut on E side.

Main_Display_Name: Black Point Rath, Pembrokeshire (Black Point; Black Scar Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Actively eroding and subsiding, especially to SW, and much lost by 1st Ed OS 1:2500 map of 1889, when curving bank c. 120m long with ditch shown to N and E. In places, the bank of shattered stone is still to 5m above the ditch and over 3m high internally.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Quadrants not defined as result of erosion.

Main_Display_Name: Broadmoor Rath, Pembrokeshire (Foxes Holes: Millhaven Camp; Mill Haven Rath; Broadmoor)
Enclosing_Summary: Curvilinear, and possibly massive boulder-faced, rampart to 2m high cuts off the headland for 100m on SE.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of massive boulder facings to (possibly rubble) bank.

Enclosing_Summary: Protected on N, S and W by the sea cliffs, with main rampart and ditch cutting off the promontory on E for 90m and running between cliff edges. Bank to 2.1m high internally, stone and rubble, and ditch c. 2m deep. Central simple gap causewayed entrance and within is slighter bank and ditch.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possible multi-phased from aerial photograph interpretation, but not proven.

Main_Display_Name: Syke Rath, Pembrokeshire (Syke Castle; Wood Farm)
Enclosing_Summary: Steep valley sides provide protection on E and S sides. On W, above a shallower stream valley, single bank, probably topped by palisade, but main defence is on N where neck of promontory cut off by three lines of ramparts. Inner and middle close-set, but outer c. 20m to N, forming an annexe or an earlier or later part of site.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly phased. Outer rampart on N forms possible annexe or an earlier or later phase of the site. Possible reoccupation in medieval period. Here inner and middle rampart remodelled to create a mound at E end of the ramparts. Hollow inside this mound suggests structure on top.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Although outer rampart on N forms possible annexe, may be an earlier or later phase of the site and as result included in quadrants.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: On W, above a shallower stream valley, single bank, probably topped by palisade.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Number of ditches not defined and assumed.

Enclosing_Summary: The headland is enclosed by a single earthen bank on the landward side. This measures 2.7m in width and 0.7m in height.

Semi-circular earthwork with double ramparts and ditches backing onto the edge of a steep sided ravine at Haydon Dean. The earthwork is approximately 130m across overall and the ditches are 28m apart.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches recorded on satellite imagery

Enclosing_Summary: Two banks with an intermediate ditch measuring approximately 73m in diameter overall. The outer bank, probably a counterscarp, has been spread by the plough in the SW and SE and measures 15m wide and 0.3m high. It is plough-levelled in the N and clipped by a road in the SW. The inner bank is badly damaged. The ditch is infilled and shallow. Crop and soil marks on satellite imagery show that it measures about 50m in internal diameter

Eliptical earthwork measuring 137m by 82m with a single rampart and ditch. Virtually ploughed out by 1946 but probably formerly of some strength. Fragments of the northern arc survived at that time as a spread bank 15m wide and 0.3m high, in the W as a slight ground swelling and in the E as a change in vegetation colour.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The construction material is unrecorded, assumed earthen as no trace of stonework can be seen on satellite imagery

Main_Display_Name: Old Castle, Milford, Pembrokeshire (Pill Rath; Old Castle Head)
Enclosing_Summary: Originally possibly bank and ditch cutting off the promontory on NW. Site now destroyed.

Two substantial semi-circular ramparts with outer ditch and counterscarp cut off the promontory on N and W, elsewhere natural scarps defend the site. Inner bank best, rising to 5m above the ditch. Outer less, rising to 1.8m above a medial ditch, with traces of outer ditch. Outer bank fades at S end where slope steeper.

N side protected by natural craggy slopes to tideway and Ferry Cwm and steep slopes to gully on E. On S two widely spaced banks and ditch cut off the promontory, inner to c. 5m above the ditch, the outer to 4m.
Naturally protected by rocky slope to tidal waterway on E side and fall to Pwllcrochan on S. Bank and ditch on N and W sides.

Sub-circular in plan comprising four large ditches with the outer ditch measuring 194m in diameter giving a total area of almost 2.95ha.  Traces of a further ditch have been identified within the enclosure which might represent an earlier palisaded phase.

Circular measuring approximately 110m in diameter and comprising two earthen ramparts and two ditches, with one medial and one outer.  The ramparts measure between 10-13.5m wide and 0.4-1.3m high. The 3m wide medial ditch has a depth of 1m below the top of the inner rampart, the outer ditch 0.8m deep below the top of the outer rampart and 5m wide.
Arcs of two concentric ditches about 3m in breadth and 12m apart.

Irregular in form with an annex in the W, its overall measurement is 103m W-S-W by 51m N-S. It is enclosed by a single earth and stone rampart with a stone facing.  The rampart stands at 3m wide and 0.5m high and where enhanced by the natural hillslope 1-2m high. No evidence of ditches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Whole site footprint approximate, measured from satellite imagery

Enclosing_Summary: Circular in plan, comprising two concentric banks, the second possibly a counterscarp, and a medial ditch. It measures 65m in diameter enclosing 0.33ha, The inner rampart survives to a height of 0.1m and is approximately 6-8m wide. The outer rampart can no longer be traced in the NE.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Described in 1734 as having a stone wall but no reference given.

Enclosing_Summary: Oval univallate enclosure approximately 0.6ha. It measures approximately 84m E-W by 86m N-S and comprises a single earth and stone rampart of between 2.5-5m wide and 0.3-1m high with an outer ditch. It is now destroyed in the S by a modern farmstead and in the E and SE a modern wall runs along the rampart causing further damage. A slight counterscarp of earth and stones has been recorded on the W and N sides, 2m wide and 0.3-0.4m high in the N, elsewhere it is very slight.

Circular in plan enclosing 0.6ha. It comprised a single earth and stone rampart and an outer ditch. An RCHME field investigation in 1955 recorded the rampart as 4m wide and 0.7m high internally and 2m above the bottom of the ditch.  The width of the ditch averaged 6m with a maximum depth of 0.7m.  Faint traces of a counterscarp were also recorded. Cropmarks on satellite imagery from 2006, however, show a ditch no more than 3m broad.

Oval in plan it measures 78m E-W by 36m N-S internally. A bank 3m wide and 0.5m high constructed with roughly dressed stones surrounds the plateau in the N, W and E, with outcropping crags to the S. A slight internal ditch up to 2.5m wide runs parallel to the bank in the N and W and is possibly a quarry ditch for stone for the rampart

Almost circular in plan with two concentric ramparts formed from parallel rows of boulders with rubble infill approximately 70m and 100m in diameter. The inner rampart measures 2.10m wide and 1.7m high and the more massive outer rampart 3.65m wide and 1.10m wide. Within the rampart core, transverse courses of stone provide greater structural stability to the rubble core of the rampart  (Tate 1862, 295-6). No evidence of ditches.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Transverse courses of stone wthin the core

Enclosing_Summary: Enclosed by an earth and stone rampart 0.3-1.2m high and 5m wide, and an external ditch 6m wide and 0.6m deep in the S.  It is uncertain if the ditch once continued around all sides.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: In the southern quadrant only.  It is uncertain if it was once continuous

Enclosing_Summary: Almost circular in plan measuring approximately 40m E-W by 44m N-S.  The earth and stone defences are univallate measuring 6m wide and standing up to 1.8m above the 5m wide ditch.  Where exposed the foundations of a stone wall two courses high have been observed within the rampart.

Main_Display_Name: West Brizlee Camp, Northumberland (West Brizlee Wood)
Enclosing_Summary: Semi-circular in plan, 54m N-S by 32m E-W.  Two earthen banks and two ditches, possibly destroyed in the W.  Inner bank 6m wide and 1.5m high above the inner ditch.  Outer bank 8-10m wide and 3m above the outer ditch. Inner ditch is 7m wide and outer ditch 6m wide.
Cropmarks of two concentric ditches (Gates, 1979), about 3m broad and up to 10m apart

The site was possibly multi-phased and originally bivallate. A third ditch was added which bulges outwards in the W creating a 0.25ha annex which is further strengthened by the addition of a fourth ditch in that area.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Two further ditches in the W
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly multiphased with up to four ditches

Enclosing_Summary: Oval in plan approximately 102m NE-SW by 58m transversely comprising a double rampart on the N, E and S sides. Now turf-covered, the ramparts utilised the natural stone outcrops and elsewhere were cut into the hillslope to form a vertical face which was stone revetted. Surviving best in the E where the ramparts are 4m wide and 1.6m high. No evidence of ditches.
Cropmark of two concentric ditches over 3m wide separated by a gap of approximately 10m.  It is estimated that the site once covered 0.98ha
The enclosure is approximately D-shaped, measuring 65m N-S by 59m E-W.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Slight bank seen on 2009 satellite imagery

Enclosing_Summary: A large ditch runs along the N side, but otherwise few earthworks remain and it is protected by natural slopes in the E, S and W.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Insufficient information to calculate an internal area

Enclosing_Summary: Oval in form it measures 70m by 45m defended by two earth and stone banks with a further bank in the SW.  It is now badly denuded with the banks surviving best in the N where the inner bank stands at up to 1m high and the outer bank up to 0.5m high.  Elsewhere they are represented by  spread scarps up to 0.3m high.  No evidence of ditches.

Main_Display_Name: S of Fenton Hill Camp, Northumberland
Enclosing_Summary: The ditches can only be seen in the NW. The diameter of the enclosure is estimated at 100m with within two ditches about 4m in breadth and set some 5m apart to enclose an area in the region of 0.9ha.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Internal area estimated by Gates at 0.95ha
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Incomplete - probably due to incomplete cropmark formation
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The HER record describes the ditches as the remains of palisade trenches
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Uncertain if ditch or palisade trench

Enclosing_Summary: Two ramparts measuring approximately 116m SW-NE by 110m transversely
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possibly an earthen bank in the N. Outer bank possibly a counterscarp
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Satellite imagery appears to show a medial ditch

Enclosing_Summary: Two ditches, observed as widely spaced concentric arcs. Interior estimated from cropmarks photographed by D W Harding
Two ditches separated by 10m, possibly a defended enclosure or ditches for a palisade
Three or more concentric ditches
Three concentric ditches set 10-15m apart which measure 120m in diameter enclosing 0.4ha.
Circular bivallate enclosure with an overall diameter of approximately 120m enclosing 0.5ha within earth and stone banks 0.4m high. No evidence for ditches.
Curvilinear enclosure of two almost circular ditches or palisades which are roughly concentric and spaced 15 to 20m apart
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Uncertain if ditches or trenches for palisades

Enclosing_Summary: Almost circular in plan it has two concentric ditches up to 4m wide and 6m apart enclosing an area some .  55m in diameter (0.23ha) and the outer ditch approximately 80m in diameter overall, giving a whole site footprint of 0.5ha.

Main_Display_Name: West Pennar Rath, Pembrokeshire (West Pennar Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Only remaining visible remains are two lengths of bank, c. 45m long and to 1.5m high, with trace of external ditch. probably defining E and W sides of the hillfort. Banks to N and S gone, but pipeline section determined site extended to S.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Banks lost on N and S, but would formerly have enclosed circuit.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Pipeline section determined site extended to S.

Enclosing_Summary: W side defended by curving earth and stone bank, now to c. 1m high, and shallow ditch, and bank badly damaged and dumped upon in early 2000's. Short length of low outer bank on NE side may be a counterscarp.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone bank. Short length of low outer bank on NE side may be a counterscarp.

Enclosing_Summary: Apart from E, defended by, now plough-levelled and discontinuous, bank and ditch. On NW bank to 1.2m high and ditch to 0.3m deep, and this is similar on S. W side beneath hedge-bank.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Appears to have been an inner enclosure/levelled area in the SW quadrant, c. 80m E-W by 60m.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by steep natural scarps on N, E and W with 70m long bank and ditch cutting off the promontory on S. Bank to c. 2m high and ditch c. 3m wide.

Main_Display_Name: Rudbaxton Rath, Pembrokeshire (Crundale Rath; The Rath)
Enclosing_Summary: Two ramparts follow the contours on the summit, widely-spaced on W. On E inner bank massive, rising to 6.5m above the ditch and 2.8m above the interior. Outer bank less, and c. 1.5m high generally.

Promontory cut off on W and S sides by massive curving bank and ditch, the bank up to 4m above the ditch. Ditch to 1.2m deep with counterscarp. Bank fades and then ends to SE before top of valley side.
Single ruinous wall
Effectively a promontory enclosure with defences visible only on the E flank
Wall cutting off access to a coastal promontory

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Lossit Point, Dun na Faing, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Promontory enclosure cut of by a single wall on the SE

Approximately circular in plan with a maximum extent of 90m it is now bisected in the E by a modern field wall which runs NW to SE and survives only in the W as two substantial banks and a medial ditch. The ditch is 6m wide and 1m deep below an 8m wide outer bank, probably a counterscarp which is steeply scarped on its outer face.  A possible palisade trench has been identified within the enclosure
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Method of construction is not recorded.  Appear as earthen banks on satellite imagery. The outer bank is probably a counterscarp

Enclosing_Summary: Only visible in the N as a double-ditched enclosure with a maximum internal E-W dimension of between 63-75m. The ditches are approximately 3m wide and spaced 14m apart.
Small sub-circular multivallate earthwork.  No further information available
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Method of construction is not recorded

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Rhinns Point, An Dun, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall possibly defending the NE approach

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Am Burg, Coul, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall cutting off access to the promontory
Cropmarks of at least three, possibly four concentric ditches in the N
Ruinous rampart across the neck of a promontory
It is enclosed at its neck on the SW by a curving earthen bank that measures up to 1.5m high.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, The Oa, Dun Mor Ghil, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single short wall blocking access to the promontory
Section excavated through defences in early 1980s by G. Williams and H. Mytum showed that ditches almost 3m deep and that banks had front and rear timber palisades.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Earth banks wth front and rear timber palisades.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Section excavated through defences in early 1980s by G. Williams and H. Mytum showed that ditches almost 3m deep.

Main_Display_Name: Faenor Gaer, Pembrokeshire (Vaenor Gaer; Vaynor Gaer)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by strong bank and ditch, best on E where 2m above the well-marked ditch with counterscarp.
Only E half survives as plough-spread, curving bank up to 1.4m high and c. 6m wide. Traces of silted ditch visible on NNE side alongside a hedge-bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of silted ditch visible on NNE side alongside a hedge-bank.

Main_Display_Name: Bush Inn Camp, Robeston Wathen, Pembrokeshire (Castle Rath)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving bank and ditch cuts off the promontory from NE-S. Best preserved on SE side, where bank to 2.6m high externally.
Defended by natural cliffs to river on E and SE sides, with bank and ditch to 5m wide and 2m deep respectively on N and on SW a 2m high scarp.

Main_Display_Name: Canaston Wood Camp, Pembrokeshire (Canaston Wood Camp; Cil Foden)
Enclosing_Summary: Straight scarp edge defines site on E, with horse-shoe shaped curving bank and ditch running from NW-SE, so cutting off the promontory, but appears levelled on N

Promontory cut off by three massive curving banks and ditches on NW, with inner bank to 4m above the ditch and 2.5m above the interior, with impressive berms 4.5 to 6m across between each bank. Middle bank and ditch not concentric with the other two, suggesting separate phase and possibly originally two widely-spaced banks with the third inserted between the two later.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Middle bank and ditch not concentric with the other two, suggesting separate phase and possibly originally two widely-spaced banks with the third inserted between the two later.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Impressive berms between each bank and ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Meherin West, Pembrokeshire (Castell Mehren West)
Enclosing_Summary: Divided in two by E-W hedge-bank. S of this boundary massive defence, with bank to 6m above a ditch and 2.3m above the interior and counterscarp, the area here overgrown with scrub and probably never ploughed. To N of the hedge-bank, defences of NE part of enclosure of similar size to S, but fades and absent N and NE of the enclosure.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Meherin East, Pembrokeshire (Castell Mehren East)
Enclosing_Summary: Plough levelled and now survives as series of scarps and low banks. Outer double banked circuit along N and E sides, c. 30m from the inner rampart/scarp, possibly running into inner circuit midway along its S side. This could form a crescent-shaped annexe, but this is unclear. No ditches visible, but probably buried features.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Plough-levelled and the quadrants are unclear as possible annexe.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: None visible, but probably buried features.

Main_Display_Name: Blaen Gywddno, Pembrokeshire (Blaengwaith-Noah Camp; Blaengwaith Noah Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Two widely-spaced curving banks, c. 25m apart and possibly up to 1.5m high, with ditches to 0.3m deep, cut off the promontory on SE and S.
Single wall cutting across the neck and extending down the E side

According to RCAHM in 1925, appears that site formerly bivallate, with substantial inner bank and ditch 21m long and outer bank c. 6m from interior with destroyed ditch. E entrance with 3m gap through inner rampart. Apart from at E end, very overgrown inner bank survives as does inner rock-cut ditch to 8m wide. Timber-built chalet has destroyed outer defence.

To N a series of substantial slightly curving ramparts cut off the headland, constructed by terracing and sculpting the steep slopes that run down to a nearby spring. Here is a formidable line of four ramparts, or scarps, the inner to c. 5m high, with some evidence of ditches, especially between the two outer lines with main entrance into fort. In addition, length of bank c. 40m long to 0.8m high, between the two inner lines, stone walls.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Quadrants estimated and only main ramparts cutting off headland defined.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Fragments of walling found, containing limestone and quartz blocks.

Enclosing_Summary: Curving angular bank and ditch, c. 55m long, cuts off the landward N and NW sides, elsewhere protected by the precipitous sea cliffs. Earth and stony bank best and highest on W, where 9m wide and to 3.5m above the rock-cut ditch (now filled with silt and rubble). TO E bank and ditch fades to natural scarp.

Main_Display_Name: Old Castle Camp, Manorbier, Pembrokeshire (Old Castle Head, Manorbier)
Enclosing_Summary: Landward defended by L-shaped bank of earth and rubble and ditch to N and W on natural slope, with a possible second closely-spaced bank and ditch on N side.
Curving rampart cuts off promontory from NE to W, standing to 1m above interior and 1.3m above ditch. Towards SE both fade.
Single bank of earth and stone and ditch defends main enclosure, bank to 2m externally, ditch now hardly visible, apart from section on E.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Only visible for c. 46m stretch on E.

Enclosing_Summary: RCAHM 1925 recorded that neck of promontory on W defended by well-preserved rampart to nearly 2m high and ditch  also to nearly 2m deep with counterscarp. Widened N entrance. By 1965 Ordnance Survey found no trace of rampart remained and this confirmed again 2006.

Single, but impressive, rampart cuts off promontory for 55m on approachable W and NW, rising to 1.6m above interior and 6m above base of ditch, with 1m high counterscarp. Ramparts curves around for short distance at either end.
No definite surface evidence for site, but S part shows as cropmark (ditch) on aerial photographs and very faint bank possibly appears to correspond with cropmark on ground.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: S part shows as cropmark on aerial photographs and very faint bank possibly appears to correspond with cropmark on ground, but uncertain.

Enclosing_Summary: Curving bank of earth and rubble and ditch cutting off the approachable promontory on N and W visible as parched cropmark on aerial photographs. Possibly unfinished.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Gwyn Ii, Pembrokeshire (Castell Gwyn Uchaf)
Enclosing_Summary: Bank spread to c. 8m wide and 0.5m high, with 0.3m deep ditch on S, fading on W. No rampart on N.
Possible bank, no detail.

Landward from sea cliffs on S defended built defence best on W. Here a curving 8m wide and 2m deep ditch, beginning at the sea cliffs at its S extremity and running onto cliff top to end abruptly on NE. Shorter length of 0.5m high bank on its W side.
Possible low bank c. 4m wide and 0.4m high seems to cuts off neck of promontory, flanked externally and internally by ditches.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Hendre Wen, Pembrokeshire (Castell Hendre-Wen; Castell Bytheg)
Enclosing_Summary: Single bank to 2m above an intermittent ditch, best on SE near a hedge-bank, but ploughed out on N quadrants.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch best on SE near a hedge-bank, but ploughed out on N quadrants.

Enclosing_Summary: An inner enclosure with two widely-spaced ramparts, possibly original enclosure of c. 58m internal diameter. SE half of this now missing, leaving a visible semi-circular area c. 58m by 45m, now undefended on the downslope SE side. However, traces of the former ramparts here can be made out on aerial photographs. Inner bank is to 1.7m high with outside ditch, the outer being c. 15m distant, also to c. 1.7m high.

Defined by concentric double bank and ditch system, with additional rampart on all but W side. Inner rampart and ditch best preserved, bank formerly to c. 4.2m high from base of ditch and 1.7m high from interior and c. 11m wide, with ditch to 5m wide, now traceable on all but W.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: A possible phased construction has been suggested by RCAHMW (Coflein), but no details.

Main_Display_Name: Molleston Back Camp, Pembrokeshire (Molleston Bank; Grove)
Enclosing_Summary: Surrounding rampart to 2m high externally has traces of outer ditch, and a second rampart lies for 40m concentric to inner rampart and 20m from it on SE side of an entrance on NE. Possible counterscarp visible at E end, but unclear.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible counterscarp visible at E end, but unclear.

Enclosing_Summary: Two walls cutting off the promontory
Single wall across the promontory
Defined by undulating bank on SW, W and NW, and pronounced scarp on N and NE. No ditch. 0.12ha.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Alt Nan Ba, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall cutting off a promontory
Defined by single bank and ditch to N, E and W and to S by steep natural slope, with no artificial re-inforcement visible. To N bank to 2m high. 0.48ha.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches survive to E and W with interior height to 1m and exterior to 2m. Ditch traceable to 0.15m deep on E, and 0.6m deep on W.

Enclosing_Summary: On NE well-preserved sweep of bank, 84m long, 3m high on the exterior, and ditch, to 1.4m deep, cuts off the promontory neck. Tip of the promontory also cut off by additional 25m bank, but whether this is medieval or prehistoric is unclear. c. 0.33ha.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Counterscarp to motte. Not included in analysis.

Enclosing_Summary: No remains visible. 1.28ha
Single wall on two sides of a headland to create a promontory enclosure
Defined by single rampart with traces of ditch. Bank to 5m high externally, with slight berm indicating position of ditch. Bank best on NE and SW sides.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Position of ditch visible as berm

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by two banks and ditches on NE, although outer ditch only visible in places and inner ditch appears disturbed. Single bank with no ditch visible elsewhere. Single rampart in NW c. 0.8m- 1m high internally and 1.3m-1.6m high externally; similar in SW. Two parallel walls of upright stone slabs are said to have been found beneath soil.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch visible on NE. Inner ditch appears disturbed.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Beinn a' Chaisteal,, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall cutting off promontory

Main_Display_Name: y Gaer, Pencarreg, Carmarthenshire (Gelli; Caer Pencarreg)
Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart completes circuit, c. 1.8m-2m high externally, with traces of ditch in places.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Erosion caused by livestock revealed rampart structure of soil and stones, and possible stretch of rear rampart facing on N.

Enclosing_Summary: Single bank, now much spread by ploughing, but survives on S and E as earthwork c. 10m wide and 0.7m high and with a slight change of slope on N and W. No evidence of ditch
Traces of rampart on NE and SE with later stone walls using the earlier line and probably the rampart stone. No trace of outer ditch.

Defined by two banks and ditches, best on S side and weakest on E where steeper slopes. Inner bank has surrounding ditch that peters out on S, with the outer bank on N, NE and NW sections with an outer ditch on N only.
Steep slopes on N, S and W form natural defence with no sign of enclosing wall which is evident on E as a curving stone wall c. 150m long, by 5m wide and 0.6m high. No ditch visible.

Defined now by a very faint trace of bank and ditch on SW and NW sides, ditch to c. 1m deep and 18m wide. Also faint trace of second outer ditch beyond NW end curving around to S, but very weak. Steep NE slope forms natural defence and no bank and ditch visible on SE.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: On SW and NW sides ditch to c. 1m deep and 18m wide. Also faint trace of second outer ditch beyond NW end curving around to S, but very weak.

Main_Display_Name: Dinefwr Castle, Carmarthenshire (Castell Dinefwr; Dynefor Castle; Dinevor Castle)
Enclosing_Summary: Built on. No details.

Main_Display_Name: y Gaer Fawr, Carn Goch, Carmarthenshire (y Gaer Fawr)
Enclosing_Summary: Massive (now fallen) stone wall with an additional stone rampart on NW surrounds the hilltop. To W main rampart is 6.5m high and 25m wide, less elsewhere to 1.5m high. Some stonework survives on W. No ditch
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Three phased construction suggested by Hogg (1974).
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site, some stonework surviving on W.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Lagavulin, An Dunan, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall around the margins of the summit
Defined by scarps above the steep natural slopes on NW and SE, with bank and ditch elsewhere.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: High stone content of banks visible.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Borraichill Mor, Argyll & Bute (Borraniebill Mor; Port Ellen; Brahunissary)
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall, probably once continuous, but lost along the outcrops on the NW flank

Main_Display_Name: y Gaer Fach,  Carn Goch, Llangadog, Carmarthenshire
Enclosing_Summary: Rather weak main dry-stone wall defines site, with second wall on the inner W side of the main wall and of laid stone slabs of different construction. No ditch.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Phased construction suggested by Hogg (1974). Rather weak main dry-stone wall defines site, with second wall on the inner W side of the main wall and of laid stone slabs of different construction, Hogg suggesting that this was unfinished and part of a second construction phase.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site. Rather weak main dry-stone wall defines site, with second wall on the inner W side of the main wall and of laid stone slabs of different construction, Hogg (1974) suggesting that this was unfinished and part of a second construction phase.

Enclosing_Summary: Bank, c. 30m long, 0.75m high and c. 5m wide, curves around W side of base of summit of hill. Faint trace of outer ditch.

Whole is a complex of banks and ditches extending to c. 260m N-S by 120m overall, with an area of 3.1ha. Within this whole  to S is an oval, single bank and ditch, enclosure measuring c. 90m N-S by 77m, with internal area c. 0.7ha. A NW-facing entrance is approached by a hollow way and an embanked 'antennae' feature that extends about 30m to W.
