Banks of this turn to define an outer enclosure circuit, banked and ditched, with internal subdivisions/additional rampart lines.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: At least two ditches, but unclear.

Enclosing_Summary: Only fragment of bank 10m long and 3m-4m high visible. Large stones visible at base of remaining bank - possible construction material. Ditch filled in.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Large stones visible at base of remaining bank - possible construction material.

Main_Display_Name: Careg Llwyd, Carmarthenshire (Gareg Llwyd; Garreg Llwyd; Mynydd Pembrey (West); Garreg Lwyd; Craig Llwyd)
Enclosing_Summary: Two lines of ramparts and ditches cut off promontory on E and S, the inner bank higher to 2m-3m high externally, and an outer bank 1m-1.5m high externally with ditch visible on E, their terminals resting on the precipitous N and W natural slopes.
Inner wall enclosing the greater part of the promontory and a second cutting off access on the NE

Bank cuts across the promontory from NNE-SSW with formerly traces of ditch at N end. Difficult to asses state of bank at present because of access problems, but formerly recorded in 1972 to 2m high on S.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: 4m section of stone revetting on E side near entrance possibly modern.

Enclosing_Summary: Level interior with outer bank on three sides, NE, E and S, with mean height of 2.4m. Scarp slope defends long NW side, RCAHM in 1917 inventory stating that bank was visible here. Traces of outer ditch to 0.3m deep at NE and SW ends; destroyed by farm track on SE.  Ordnance Survey, in 1976, found traces of additional bank at N end, 0.7m high internally, with scarp 2.2m high and berm 5m wide on the outside.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: More than one phase of construction proposed by OS because of irregular form, but not proven.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Bank suggested by RCAHM in 1917 probably correct, but not visible now.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of outer ditch to 0.3m deep at NE and SW ends, with possible outer ditch on the second N bank found by OS 1976.

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Port Ellen, Borraichill Mor, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Thick wall cutting off the promontory formed by the W end of a low ridge

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Dun Cheapasaidh Mor, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single robbed wall

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Dun Nosebridge, Argyll & Bute (Neriby; Dun Noesbridge; Mulindry; Upper Laggan Valley)
Enclosing_Summary: Three roughly concentric ramparts and ditches forming tiers stepping down the flanks of the ridge on the NE, NW and SW
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The outer enclosure was possibly a freestanding defence in its own right of 0.18ha

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Dun Guaidhre, Argyll & Bute (Dun Guaire; Kilmeny)
Enclosing_Summary: Three concentric ramparts and ditches, the outer accompanied by a counterscarp bank, and the inner encircling the summit
Twin ditches, presumably accompanied by upcast ramparts
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Only partly known through aeial photography

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Bridgend, Borraichill Mor, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single Wall

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Rubha Bhollsa, Argyll & Bute (Rubha Bholsa)
Enclosing_Summary: Lengths of wall blocking access to the promontory
Single wall round most of the summit and fragments of an outer wall on the N
Single wall cutting off the only point of access to this promontory

Main_Display_Name: Oronsay, Dun Domhnuill, Argyll & Bute (Oronsay House)
Enclosing_Summary: Single stone wall , possibly with an outwork on the E
Single wall cutting off promontory
Two wide-spaced walls cutting across the neck
Single wall cutting off the promontory and extending along the S and E margins
Single wall
Two walls round most of the circuit
One continuous inner wall with an outlying wall on the E and S

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Fang a' Chaisteil, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: One wall probably encircling the summit area but no longer visible on the SE, with two outer walls on the leading edges of lower terraces on the NE

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Lagavulin, Barr An T-Seann Duine, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall intermittently visible between the outcrops around the margins of the summit of this rocky headland
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The medial wall-face visible within the thickness of the wall in a gully on the NW possibly indicates  multiperiod construction rather than an internal structure to help stabilise the wall

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Dun Nan Gall, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Three walls cutting across a promontory

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Trudernish Point, Argyll & Bute (Dun Thrudernish; Claggain Bay; Aros Bay)
Enclosing_Summary: Three walls cutting across the neck of a promontory

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Mullach Ban, An Dun, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: single rampart or wall
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: For the purposes of the Atlas the interior is taken to be that of the outer enclosure
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The dun and its outwork are excluded

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Creagan na Ceardaich Moire, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Probably continuous but no trace survives on the SW

Enclosing_Summary: Rectilinear in plan, it is formed by two close-set ditches with a spacing of about 10m

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Dun An Rubha Bhuidhe, Argyll & Bute (Dun An Rudha Bhuide; Claggain Bay; Ardtalla)
Enclosing_Summary: Three walls cutting off a promontory

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Loch Nan Clach, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall, probably originally continuous

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Kintour, Dun Beag, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall everywhere exept the SE

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Port Ellen, The Ard, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall round the landward margin of the promontory, with fragments of an outer wall at one end

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Carraig Bun Aibhne, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single ruinous wall visible on W and E margins of the promontory

Main_Display_Name: Islay, Port Chubaird, Dunan Buidhe, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall visible on the S margin of the promontory
Single wall everywhere except the cliff-edge on the SW

Main_Display_Name: Jura, Dunan An Raoil, Argyll & Bute (Dun An Roail; Crackaig)
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall around the margin but very heavilly robbed

Main_Display_Name: Jura, Creag An Dunain, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Wall reduced to a band of rubble is visible around the margins of the knoll everywhere except the SE
Single wall heavily robbed but with several runs of outer face, which can be traced round parts of the summit
Traces of a single wall cutting of the tip of a low ridge

Main_Display_Name: Jura, Ardmenish, An Dunan, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: A complex series of defensive walls

Main_Display_Name: Caerau Clungwyn, Carmarthenshire (Caerau, Newchurch; Caerau Clyngwyn)
Enclosing_Summary: Unusual layout, as uses two parallel steep slopes at narrower NE and SW ends of the site as part of defences, with a strong bank and ditch, best on NE, where bank to c. 1.8m high and ditch to 6m wide and 1m deep. Possible counterscarp, but uncertain. Mainly natural defences along the longer SE and NW sides
Essentially defined by single massive rampart and intermittent ditch, especially on E, an additional rock-cut scarp and ditch also visible, especially on N side.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Phased construction proved by DAT in 1980's, with earlier 1ha enclosure on NE two-thirds of the site suggested, with occupation layer pre-dating rampart, and providing C14 dates of  360_60BC and 150_70BC. But rampart itself probably simple dump, perhaps with some form of revetment, of one phase only.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Rampart itself probably simple dump, perhaps with some form of revetment, of one phase only. Not full excavation.

Enclosing_Summary: Linear bank and ditch, 60m long, 12m wide and 3m high cuts off the NE side, with ditch rock-cut 3m wide and 2m deep. the steep slopes providing defence elsewhere.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Estimated area on rounded triangular promontory

Enclosing_Summary: Segment of curved bank, and traces of ditch, c. 36m long, 10m wide and 0 2.4m high, recorded when OS visited the site in 1976, cutting off the rising ground of promontory on SW, which measures c. 56m across. By 1984 most bulldozed and by 2007 no earthworks visible in the pasture on SW. It is possible that earthworks still remain in the scrub and wood to NE, but, as it is so overgrown further detail is not forthcoming at present. Elsewhere steep natural scarps provide defence.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Trace of ditch possible to NE.

Enclosing_Summary: Roughly concentric bank, 1m-2m high, cuts off the promontory on NE, with wide 10m-12m gap at W end, probably site of entrance. Steep natural slopes form defence on E and W sides. No trace of outer ditch, but possible buried feature now.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No trace of outer ditch, but possible buried feature now.

Enclosing_Summary: Defended by a single slight bank to 2m high externally, with outer terrace, c. 2m wide, being probable position of ditch. Traces of possible second scarp to SE. No ditch visible on NE where slopes steepest. On gentler SW side fine series of ramparts and ditches around entrance, reaching c. 4.2m high. Entrance has two large ramparts, with flat terraces between. Additional outer scarp on W just visible, and number of scarps in the wood on E, possibly part of defences. Around N angle traces of possible scarp of another ditch beyond that belonging to main rampart.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Quadrants estimated and do not take into account any possible additions on N or E
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly three, but at least two.

Main_Display_Name: yr Hen Castell, Llanfihangel-Ar-Arth, Carmarthenshire (Hen Castell)
Enclosing_Summary: In 1968 the Ordnance Survey found a substantial single bank and ditch on all sides, except on NW directly above the river where natural slopes provided adequate defence, but by 2007 DAT found that this had been much reduced and ditch only a trace, either hardly visible on E.

Steep natural scarp above the river on NW, but rampart and ditch elsewhere. This rose to 2.9m high on E and SW, with ditch to 1m depth when visited by Ordnance Survey in 1968 and by DAT in 2007. On NE and SW the curving bank terminated where met the steep slopes leading to the river below.

Defined by two ramparts and ditches cutting off the promontory from NNW-SSE, with natural scarps defence elsewhere, with the outer rampart, c. 3m-4m high, higher than the inner at c. 2m high. Ditch to outer rampart still substantial.
Three ramparts with intermediate ditches, but only fragments survive around the E
Enclosing_Gang_Working_Comments: RCAHMS investigators suggested that minor irregularities in the lines of the ditches reflect gang working
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Possibly a third, outer ditch, observed at one point on the W

Enclosing_Summary: Three walls forming an enclosure round a knoll backing onto the cliff-edge
Defended by the very steep natural defences on E, but on moderate W outer bank to 3.4m high with traces of inner bank. No ditch.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Two weak banks or outworks splaying out from entrance not included in quadrants.

Enclosing_Summary: To N, E and W steep slopes provide good defence and only slight bank constructed here. To W substantial bank and ditch cuts across the ridge with bank to c. 3.3m high, with traces of ditch at S end.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly two periods, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Main enclosure defined by bank 2m-3m high with traces of external ditch. Smaller enclosure scarped.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly two phases of larger enclosure with smaller in NW quadrant superimposed.

Enclosing_Summary: Possible part of an enclosure with earthworks, some natural, but others a possible defensive bank to 0.25m-0.3m high.

Defined by rampart and ditch, reduced to possible slight scarp (or none) above the very steep NW slope, with additional curving rampart and ditch on SW. Limited excavations, 1967-8 (de Quincey 1970) found  outer ditch flat-bottomed, and inner ditch V-shaped and cut c. 1.5m into solid rock. Ramparts were of rubble, inner revetted inside and out with dry-stone walling, outer with massive vertical slabbing - latter technique also around base of inner rampart near the entrance.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Limited excavations, 1967-8 (de Quincey 1970) found  outer ditch flat-bottomed, and inner ditch V-shaped and cut c. 1.5m into solid rock. Ramparts were of rubble, inner revetted inside and out with dry-stone walling, outer with massive vertical slabbing - latter technique also around base of inner rampart near the entrance.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Limited excavations, 1967-8 (de Quincey 1970) found outer ditch flat-bottomed and inner ditch V-shaped.

Enclosing_Summary: Possible evidence of semi-circular bank and ditch on the land approach to the castle on N, S and W, with the steep natural slopes on SE side forming the defence. Earthworks of hillfort incorporated in castle defences, and now impossible to determine area, extent or vallation of site. These medieval/Iron Age earthworks best on W of castle, as three lines of bank and ditch, with further line of bank and ditch 70m to W.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Possible evidence of semi-circular bank and ditch on the land approach to the castle on N, S and W, with the steep natural slopes on SE side forming the defence. Earthworks of hillfort incorporated in castle defences, and now impossible to determine area, extent or vallation of site.

Enclosing_Summary: Thick walled fortification on the summit of the ridge is considered a later dun constructed from the ruins of an earlier fort
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The inner dun (0.03ha) is omitted from the defences
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Reduced to no more than a scarp

Main_Display_Name: Castell Gorwyn, Castell Gorwyn Farm, Carmarthenshire (Parc y Castell)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined on site by much reduced and spread earthwork bank to 0.3m high and c. 10m wide, best on uphill side to W.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-y-Gar, Llanpumsaint, Carmarthenshire (Pen y Gaer; Pen y Gar)
Enclosing_Summary: Single bank and ditch cuts off the promontory on NE side, overlain by hedgebank with trees and bracken. Bank c. 45m long and to 1.9m high where best on N and only to 0.6m on S. Ditch now shallow hollow.
Single wall
Inner stone wall, within an outer defence with at least two ramparts
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Footprint based on an assumption that the outer defence uncovered by excavation on the W extended around the rest of the circuit
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Beneath the tumble from the inner wall were burnt wood and twigs possibly from a wattle superstructure.

Enclosing_Summary: Defended on the easily approachable E side by single  curving bank and ditch c. 70m long cutting off the promontory. Bank now spread by ploughing to 1m high at N and and 0.5m high at S. In 1967 OS recorded bank at 1.8m high. Ditch now only visible as a slight linear hollow. Two crossbanks and ditches visible in interior across site as low earthworks, to 65m and 120m W of main rampart. Possibly vestiges of earlier activity.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch now only visible as a slight linear hollow.

Enclosing_Summary: Naturally protected by the steep natural slopes to N, SE and W, a curving ploughed-down rampart and ditch, c. 150m long, joins the two narrow stream valleys to NE and SW. Two additional outer defensive banks protect site to W.  Inner bank to 1.2m high, with good outer ditch. Middle bank to c. 60m long, has traces of ditch, whilst 60m long outer bank has well-defined ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Inner and outer banks have well-defined ditches, middle bank has a trace visible.

Enclosing_Summary: Protected by the steep slopes to E and S and by curving ploughed-down rampart, c. 150m long NE-SW and to 1.3m high, with no ditch visible.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch visible. Possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank and traces of ditch, best on SW, where bank to 1.8m externally. To SE bank becomes a scarp, then fades to a mere break of slope, with no trace of ditch.

Site almost ploughed -down, but on SW ditch, c. 8m wide and c. 0.4m deep, with slight trace of inner bank runs from scarp edge for c. 30m turning to NE before fading. To NE curving hedge line continues line of perimeter bank to the scarp edge.

Defined by two main earth and rubble banks, circular in plan, the inner rampart c. 35m diameter, the outer c. 60m diameter.  Area not defined and ditches hardly visible. Possible third low bank and ditch, to 0.9m deep, beyond the outer rampart on NE.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Possible third bank on NE. Levelled on W.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Inner banks ditches hardly visible, but outer ditch on NE to 0.9m deep.

Enclosing_Summary: Site's NE side abuts the scarp edge of the ridge. W half of site completely flattened, but traces of bank to c. 0.5m high and ditch to c. 1m deep on E.
Series of walled enclosures, of which only the innermost has a complete circuit
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The fourth line of enclosure here, which does not appear to be sited tactically and is incompletely known, may take in in excess of 2ha
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: The outermost line has been excluded

Enclosing_Summary: Complete inner circuits in two phases partial multivallation on one side
Single rampart around the landward side, with outer ramparts across the neck
Single wall cutting off a promontory
Single wall forming a complete circuit; several runs of face are visible, particularly on the N, where it measures 2.4m in thickness

Three massive bank with intervening ditches cut off the promontory on the vulnerable SW side. Inner bank to c. 6m-7m high and ditcch to c. 7m-8m wide At N tip, bank and ditch mark limit of interior in addition to steep natural slopes.
Single stone wall
Defended by single bank and ditch, the bank to 2.5m high externally, with ditch to 0.6m deep on E, less clear elsewhere. Scarped terrace on SW. Hedge bank on E may be re-used outer bank
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Hedge bank on E may be re-used outer bank; not included in quadrants.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch to 0.6m deep on E, less clear elsewhere.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by an arcing crescent-shaped, but incomplete, bank from SW through to NE quadrants c. 1.5m high and traces of ditch, with natural defence on the steep SE above the Taf estuary. On E bank meets the steep slope, but on SW stops c. 40m short. Geophysical
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Bank and ditch stops short of steep slope on SW, possibly indicating site unfinished.

Main_Display_Name: Woodreefe Castle, Carmarthenshire (Marros Castle; The Castle, Marros; The Castle, Woodreefe)
Enclosing_Summary: Earth and stone curving rampart, up to 2.5m high and 6m-7m wide, cuts off the promontory from NE-SW, It has a 1.5m wide flattish top. Outer face nearly vertical above a shallow flat-bottomed ditch c. 6m wide and c. 1.5m deep average and 3m where meets the gorge on N end.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Shallow flat-bottomed ditch c. 6m wide and c. 1.5m deep average and 3m where meets the gorge on N end.

Enclosing_Summary: N and E sides overlain by hedgebanks, but a line of curving shallow ditch, to 0.4m deep shows the W side of site.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Curving shallow ditch, to 0.4m deep shows the W side of site.

Enclosing_Summary: Curving massive bank, c. 5m high, with ditch, c. 1.3m deep and 4m wide, cuts off the promontory from NW-SE, with much weaker counterscarp bank, best on NW, and to 1m high on W and only 0.3m on E. Bank peters out as curves SE, but ends abruptly on W.

Single rubble bank and ditch defines site, in 1975 Ordnance Survey recording as 1m high and outer ditch 1.5m deep. By 2008, DAT recorded bank only to 0.3m high and ditch hardly visible. Bank best on W, the E side very much robbed.
On W triple bank and ditch system cuts off the promontory. Best preserved on S, but outermost ditch not visible here. Outer two banks fade towards N side where steep natural slopes begin.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outermost ditch not visible on S.

Main_Display_Name: Gigha, Dunan An T-Seasgain, Argyll & Bute
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall with one run of inner face and several of outer, in one place on the SW standing 1.2m high in five courses.
Three ramparts, the innermost and outermost of which are continuous on all sides, while the middle one peters out along the NE flank.

Main_Display_Name: Parc-y-Gaer, Colston, Carmarthenshire (Parc y Gaer; Pant Glas; Parccyn)
Enclosing_Summary: Single bank and ditch cuts off the promontory on the NW, with steep natural slopes on W and S. Bank ploughed on E for c. 28m, the 25m on N better preserved with external height of 2m above base of ditch. Ditch also ploughed in past and now slight hollow all around the circuit.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch ploughed in past and now slight hollow all around the circuit.

Enclosing_Summary: Bank and ditch surround, the former to 1.7m above the latter, with counterscarp to 0.5m high on N, though much reduced on E and S.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Counterscarp to 0.5m high on N, though much reduced on E and S.

Enclosing_Summary: Three lines of defence cutting off the promontory on easily approachable SSW. Most of site within deciduous woodland and scrub, but outer rampart, c. 65m long ESE-WSW, lay mostly in pasture field and this part was removed in 1984, when it remained as a spread of stone and clay. Its W end remains in overgrown woodland. Middle and short inner rampart (c. 25m long) and ditches remain well-preserved in woodland. Wide gaps between all three ramparts; between outer and middle 25m, between middle and inner 8m. Ditches now shallow, but banks to 5m high above.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Three former ramparts on SW, part of outer removed 1984.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch possible, but not defined.

Enclosing_Summary: Strong curving rampart, c. 90m long, with ditch cuts off the promontory on the easily approachable NW side. Bank rises to c 5m above the ditch and 2.3m above the interior, the ditch being c. 10m wide and 2m deep. A counterscarp bank is weaker.

Main_Display_Name: Pen y Gaer Fawr, Penlan, Carmarthenshire (Pengare Vawr; Pangare Vach)
Enclosing_Summary: DAT in 2008 found traces of curving bank to 0.3m high left on N side of enclosure, with a curving hedge bank possibly defining S side. No ditch.

Now effectively cropmark only, but bank just visible as a slight rise 15-20m wide and ditch as a slight hollow. Prior to destruction site was univallate and roughly circular in form of c. 85m diameter. Formerly single strong rampart of shattered stone and earth with ditch on the N and W sides, the bank to 4m high external, and weak bank on the SE overlooking the steep slope.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Site now levelled. Quadrants as prior to this.

Enclosing_Summary: Two banks cut off the level approach to the promontory on the NW. Now much reduced by ploughing, but curving inner bank and ditch best preserved for c. 86m length, to external height of 1.5m, although internal height only c. 0.3m. Outer bank and ditch are just visible as slight bank, particularly on W.
Curving rampart c. 110m long cuts off the promontory on the NW, easily approachable side.

Site defined by ditch across the narrow part of a rock projection that overlooks the valley below. Much ploughed in past and in 1985 Dyfed Archaeological Trust recorded that bank and ditch ploughed-out on E and S and hardly visible. But bank and ditch still on W and NW. Further damaged by pipeline.

Main_Display_Name: Cefn Gaer, Carmarthenshire (Bron y Gaer; Bronygaer)
Enclosing_Summary: Visible as cropmark, but just visible on site as low earthwork, no more than 0.4m high, no ditch.
Now a low earthwork bank incorporating rock outcrop at W end. Ploughed at E end. No ditch.
Defined by stone-revetted rampart or walls on all sides apart from on N where additional rampart and ditch where access easiest

Single rampart, to 2.5m high externally, encloses c. 0.25ha of the knoll, with additional length of bank and internal ditch running tangentially to main body of the enclosure on NW. Ditch traceable, especially on N and E.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch traceable, especially on N and E.

Enclosing_Summary: Single curving rampart c. 250m long follows the contour of the hill and cuts off the promontory on NE and enclosing interior area 4ha. Trace of internal bank c. 150m long runs N-S parallel with W end of the promontory. No ditches evident.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Trace of internal bank c. 150m long runs N-S parallel with W end of the promontory.

Enclosing_Summary: Although ploughed-out, two banks now only visible on the W-facing scarp edge side extending for c. 180m long by 30m-40m wide from inner ditch to outer bank, with sequence of: infilled inner ditch, degraded inner bank, another ditch and then outer shale bedrock bank c. 2m high.

Single bank and ditch roughly follow 200m contour, best on E where bank to 1m high and 3m wide, with outer ditch 4m wide. On N and W sides, possible that defences scarped to accentuate the effect. Hedge line on W side. possible traces of another outer bank on S side (in adjoining field).
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: On N and W sides, possible that defences scarped to accentuate the effect. Hedge

Main_Display_Name: Danycerrig, Carmarthenshire (Dan y Cerig; Dan-y-Cerig; Cerig Fawr)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank to 2m high, with no evidence of ditch visible to E where access gained by DAT in 2007, but possibly exists to NW.
On site outer ditch clear and defining N edge of the enclosure; best at SE end where rock-cut and c. 2.75m wide. Inner bank to this ditch visible and and traces of outer bank at E end.
Single trench
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Supposedly a marker trench, but there is no evidence to support this interpretation, and superficially it is more akin to palisade trench, though a trial trench failed to reveal any packing.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Silted rock-cut trench, in which no evidence of stone packing was found, leading to its identification as the marker for a rampart that was never built.

Enclosing_Summary: Single wall cutting off three sides of a rocky promontory
Single rampart drawn round the margin of this hilltop
Single wall
Two ramparts encircling the hillock

Main_Display_Name: Saddell House, Argyll & Bute (Saddell House Policies)
Enclosing_Summary: Single wall with outer face in one place 1.1m high in three courses
single continuous wall with outer wall on the NW quarter, where there is also a possible annexe or hornwork
Single wall enclosing the summit
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The dun on the SW end of the fort is heavily vitrified and displays massive vitrifaction

Enclosing_Summary: Aerial photographs show circular cropmark ditch and hint of concentric second ditch on NE side (visible as a very low earthwork on the ground). On site defined by Iow earthwork bank, best preserved on SE where to 0.3m high.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Possibly two ramparts, but not defined.

Enclosing_Summary: Two curving rampart cuts off promontory on NE enclosing area c. 0.5ha. Outer bank to  c.1.2m, inner bank to c.1m high and with visible outer ditch and c. 27m between the two banks.

Defined by right-angled rock-cut ditch with internal bank running across E side of the ridge. Ditch to c. 4m wide and 0.5m deep, and bank to 0.5m high and 3m wide. Bank and ditch fades as runs into steep flanking slopes, but slight earthwork terrace running around SW end of the ridge, obscured by hedgebank. Traces of slight scarp, possibly footings for palisade, along N side where slope steepest. C. 75m to E of the right- angled ditch and bank, rocky outcrop possibly artificially steepened to provide outer line of defence.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Traces of slight scarp, possibly footings for palisade, along N side where slope steepest.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Defined by right-angle rock-cut ditch with internal bank running across E side of the ridge. Ditch to c. 4m wide and 0.5m deep, and bank to 0.5m high and 3m wide. Bank and ditch fades as runs into steep flanking slopes,

Enclosing_Summary: Elongated oval in shape with single earthwork rampart on N side and defended by natural slopes on precipitous S. Rampart narrows along spine of the ridge at NE end and ends in a cross bank and rock-cut ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Rock-cut ditch with cross-bank on NE.

Enclosing_Summary: Site  almost destroyed and mostly only a cropmark which shows cropmark shows outline of enclosure and possible partial survival inner rampart and other ditch lines that may represent an annexe or internal divisions. On site visit by DAT in 2008 found seemingly complex arrangement of ditches as shallow curvilinear features to 0.3m deep. Some possible banks, but barely discernible.

Main_Display_Name: Gilman Point and Napps Circle, Carmarthenshire (Gilman Camp; Nappo Camp; Napps Circle; Napps Camp; Napp's Head; Napp's Head Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Triple system of defences cutting off the headland on the N. Curving outer bank c. 2m high internally, 3.3m high externally and outer rock-cut ditch c. 1-1.5m deep. Outer defence forms highest point of promontory. Inner defences slighter than outer bank and ditch, but still visible on site as earthwork banks running SW down the slope towards the cliff.
Remains of stone rampart. No further details. Slope defence on SE.

Plough-reduced low rampart on W, but substantial rampart with outer ditch below elsewhere. Beyond a second ditch defends shallower saddle of ground on E and S. Both ditches only recognised from 1995 aerial photography in parch-mark conditions (RCAHMW neg. ref. 955142-55). Whether a second rampart stood between the two ditches not proven, although likely, and in that case the fort bivallate. However, parch marks show possible traces of palisade trench on outside lip of inner ditch, at the foot of main rampart. Best preserved banks on S tip of site. Main single rampart walled with dry-stone, with well-preserved stretches visible.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Site possibly bivallate, but not visible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Main single rampart walled with dry-stone, with well-preserved stretches visible. Parch-marks show possible traces of palisade trench on outside lip of inner ditch, at the foot of main rampart.

Enclosing_Summary: Traces of curving bank to 2m high externally visible from the edge of steep natural on NE. On SE bank with outer ditch followed by an outer bank and ditch to 0.5m high. No trace of defence on W side of above steep natural slopes of Allt Fawr wood. It is possible that the site was more complex than has been envisaged and that there were three lines of defence rather than two. In addition a small ditch across the interior may indicate an earlier enclosure, but not proven.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Probable phased construction, but no details.

Enclosing_Summary: Single wall round the margin
Single wall about 4.5m in thickness with well preserved faces 1m high in some sectors, and an outlying wall cutting off access from the SW
Single wall
Single wall
Bank to c. 4m high and ditch on N side, where weakest. Less prominent around rest of circuit where can be traces as low bank and terrace where ditch was.
Defined by low bank, to 1.2m high, topped by ruinous field wall on S side. No ditch visible on site, but aerial photographs show ditch on N side.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Aerial photographs show ditch on N side.

Enclosing_Summary: Single wall around the margin with additional wall at the SW end
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: The inner dun has a burnt wall and vitrifaction

Main_Display_Name: Gaer Wen, Pen-y-Graig, Ceredigion (Garn Wen, Llandysul)
Enclosing_Summary: Curving stone walls cut off the promontory on E and SE, with natural steep slope defence on N, SW and W sides.  No ditch visible.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Bank of stone with very little earth.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by earth and stone bank to 1m high and 3m wide with traces of outer ditch on E. Possible revetment. Second line of rampart at the foot of slope enclosed an extra 0.6ha.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth or earth and stone bank. Possible revetment.

Enclosing_Summary: To the SW of the duns crowning the summit, two walls cut off access from this direction.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The duns are not included in the vallation

Enclosing_Summary: Continuous inner wall with fragments of an outer round three sides
Single wall cutting off the approaches from the NNE
Single bank and ditch. Small scale excavation shows stone footings of a possible box rampart associated with burnt material.

Main_Display_Name: Rubha Cladh Eoin, Argyll & Bute (Loch Sween; Port Lunna)
Enclosing_Summary: Single thick wall cuts off the promontory from the ENE
Bank c. 18m long, 12m wide and 1m high  and silted ditch cross narrowest part of promontory defend moderate sloping S side.
Bank to 1.7m above interior and 5m plus above base of a rock-cut ditch faces rising ground and cuts off promontory on N and E, with counterscarp for short length. Natural cliff defence on S and W.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Penrhos, Ceredigion (Caer Pen-Rhos; Castell Penrhos)
Enclosing_Summary: Defended by bank and ditch with evidence on aerial photographs of partial outer ditch on E. The medieval ringwork is more massive and is built across the defences of the fort on the SE. It is bounded by a rock-cut ditch on S and W sides.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Original rampart stonework noted along S rampart.

Main_Display_Name: Pendinas Lochtyn, Ceredigion (Pen Dinas Lochtyn; Pendinaslochtyn; Pendinaslochdin; Pendinaslochdyn)
Enclosing_Summary: On N and E sides, where slopes steepest, bank 5m wide and to 5m high is evident with no ditch visible. On S side strong bank  has external ditch. To SE defences nearly bivallate with bank, ditch and bank. W now up to 2.5 m high with traces of external ditch.

Strong defences and almost rectangular in shape, with substantial curving bank, to 2.5m high interior, and ditch on the S and E and natural scarped slopes on the N and W. bank best on E, gradually becoming less on S and SW.
C. 30m NW of the rocky face of saddle, bank, c. 5m wide and 0.8m high with ditch on SE and counterscarp bank SE of the ditch, cuts off the promontory  NE-SW, stopping short of steep NE slope.

Field boundaries have part-fossilised any ramparts on S and E sides, but on S possible that the steep slope is all, and on E a 3m high sharp break of slope, possibly artificially steepened, appears to replace a rampart, with no ditch visible. On N and W very spread bank up to 15m wide and to 0.7m high, with silted or filled-in ditch.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Quadrants estimated and possible natural slope on S.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch only visible on N and W.

Main_Display_Name: Pen Coed-Foel Camp, Ceredigion (Pencoed y Foel)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by degraded bank, ditch and counterscarp circa 12m plus overall and to 2.5m high.
Defined by steep natural slopes above the river on the SE, supplemented by a slight bank. Elsewhere a curving bank and ditch. Substantial ramparts 2-3m above interior and 5m above bottom of ditch. NE
Enclosed by a bank and ditch, double on the N, and weakest, side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Trace of stone revetment to inner bank.

Enclosing_Summary: The neck is traversed by two sets of earthwork defences. The inner comprises two large banks and ditches, the outer two earthen banks and an intervening ditch. The inner of these outer banks is at least 5m high, while the outer is c. 3m high and c. 5m wide; the ditch is c. 3m wide and c. 4m deep.
Two curving banks, c. 2m in height, with ditches, c. 90m long, cross the easily approachable E side, enclosing c. 0.3ha.
On E bank and ditch cuts off the promontory. Bank c. 2.5m above ditch bottom which is c. 0.8m deep and 3m wide.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Cadwgan, Cellan, Ceredigion (Caer Morrice; Gelli-Gaer Hillfort)
Enclosing_Summary: Egg-shaped main enclosure to NW defined by heavily robbed stone wall and ditch, now scree-like, but traces of original rampart face visible. Possible traces of dividing wall enclosing higher SE part of this main enclosure. A less substantial outer circuit encloses an area c. 60m across on E and S sides of main enclosure, with entrance on W, to N of which is possible oval stony banked and terraced enclosure, c. 36m across, all abutting the main circuit as an annexe of 0.85ha. Entrance
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Total internal area of 1.29ha includes the annexe. Probable phased construction of rampart in places.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Defined by heavily robbed stone wall and ditch.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Structure of rampart investigated revealing variations in phased construction of walls of boulders of varying size and better quality coursed build and fine dry-stone walling.

Enclosing_Summary: Strong single bank and ditch with counterscarp, much reduced on N.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: The interior is divided by a cross-bank, interpreted by Hogg (1962) as evidence of phased construction, but not proven.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Counterscarp much reduced on N as bank.

Enclosing_Summary: Hedge-line divides site into NE and SW fields. Spread bank to 0.3m high, with traces of external ditch define site. Best in SW field and hardly visible in NE. Counterscarp to SW and NW.
The promontory is enclosed to the S by a single bank running 37m E and W across the neck. It is an old field fence
There are no recorded earthworks, ditches or ramparts
Defined by bank to 0.6m high and 8m across on W, less elsewhere, no ditch visible.Rampart overlain by field boundary tree banks on N and E. Entrance
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch visible. Probably buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank ditch and counterscarp, more prominent on more accessible N side, where best for c. 30m on NW to 18m wide in total and to 4m - 5m high. Reduced to scarp on S and ditch mostly silted. Possible revetment as outer face of rampart steep.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Best on NW side; ditch mostly silted elsewhere.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible revetment as outer face of rampart steep.  Counterscarp more prominent on N as bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch mostly silted apart from N.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Moeddyn Fach, Ceredigion (Castell Moedd Yn Fach; Castell Moeddin Fach)
Enclosing_Summary: Substantial bank, c. 2m high, and ditch cuts across the sloping 48m deep promontory for c. 35m on N side; overall 13m wide.

Main_Display_Name: New Cross Camp, Ceredigion (Gors Hillfort; Cefn y Gaer)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank to 1m high and traces of ditch
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possible phased construction, the first 0.35 ha in area.

Enclosing_Summary: Bank, 170m long and c. 3m high and c. 15 wide at base, and ditch cut across the promontory on N from W-E, and continue around edge at E end, with an additional bank and ditch 9m from main rampart, running for c. 75m, so forming additional defence on level neck of promontory. Inner ditch rock-cut here. Rampart well-preserved at W end, where it inturns and is flanked by good rock-cut ditch terminal. It is possible that there is some scarping on E, S and W sides of promontory,
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches at E, inner rock-cut.

Enclosing_Summary: Bank, to 2.4m high, and ditch c. 0.7m deep, cut across the narrowest point of the promontory on the E, and continue less strongly for about halfway along N and S sides. Impressive facade. Traces of quarry ditch to N.
Main enclosure defined by single rampart to 2m high and 15m across.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: 0.45ha main fort. 0.14 annexe - 1.3 ha total including additional palisaded annexe.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches to annexe. None defined to main enclosure; possibly buried feature.

Main_Display_Name: Gaer Fawr, Llanilar, Ceredigion (Pen y Caerau)
Enclosing_Summary: Double bank and ditch on N, curving round to E and W, where outer bank fades and defences single. Rampart slightest where steep slope on S. Inner rampart of shale rubble and clay with traces of stone revetment visible where eroded, rising to c. 4m high and 10m wide. Traces of stone capping on rampart top to SE. Remains of outer rock-cut ditch on SE side probably continued at least around rest of E and N sides. On W side rampart smaller and more of a scarp bank.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Inner rampart of shale rubble and clay with traces of stone revetment visible where eroded. Traces of stone capping on rampart top to SE. Hogg (1994, 261) suggests that perhaps the outer rampart is an unfinished addition, but this is questionable. Main

Enclosing_Summary: Defended on W by two widely-spaced ramparts, and on E by single rampart, with Interspace of c. 30m between banks on W side, no evidence of ditch. Ramparts average c. 1m high and fade to N and S, giving the site an unfinished look and possibly incomplete.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts average c. 1m high and fade to N and S.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch defeined; possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by curving bank on N side, to 3m high and 6m wide, but no obvious rampart on S side, no evidence for ditches. Total past planting of conifers (part cleared) has obscured detail, making interpretation difficult,
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch defined. Possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Single bank to 2.5 m high on S and E reducing to N. No rampart on the precipitous W. To E rampart curves around at S point and back N for short distance to a minor summit dominating the SE approaches. No evidence for ditches.
Simple bank c. 6m wide and 2m high externally encloses rocky interior. No evidence of ditches.
Aerial photographs show a single ditch around the whole circuit, no evidence of a bank/rampart, completely ploughed away.
Rampart, c. 20m long, 5m wide and to 1m high cuts off the spur on the NE and E side. Elsewhere possibly scarped, but no details.

Strong defences of two concentric banks and ditches with circa 6m interspace, but outer rampart absent on the steep SE and single scarp only. Inner bank to 3.5m high and c.17m wide, outer rampart to 2m high and 10m wide. Berm between inner ditch and outer rampart.

Defined by bank to 3m high externally following the contours of the hill. Possible second bank suggested curving around NE, NW and W sides, c. 30m from inner circuit, but this could be associated with mining features and therefore not proven. No ditch defined.
Defended by bank to 4m high with buried ditch now only showing as a terrace on N, S and W, but on E two additional banks.

Main_Display_Name: Capel Bangor Camp, Ceredigion (Caerau; Castell yr Aber)
Enclosing_Summary: Traces of bank and ditch on N and E, with scarps on S. Bank on E c. 0.5m high
Defended by bank and ditch, bank to 1.5m above ditch, which only visible on E side. Ploughing resulted in defences on W side  much reduced.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch only visible on E side.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-y-Darren, Ceredigion (Darren Camp; Daren Camp; Banc y Darren; Banc-y-Darren)
Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart to 4.5m high defined enclosure, single ditch.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Style of defences suggest possible phased construction, but no details.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Revetment evidence at W gate, exposed by severe erosion within gate terminal.

Main_Display_Name: Lletty-Evan-Hen, Ceredigion (Pen-y-Castell; Pen y Castell; Hen Gaer)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by strong bank and ditch with slight counterscarp, c. 12m wide overall, with bank to 3m high, especially each side of simple gap entrance on NE, but generally weak. Traces of walling visible on rampart in places. Circuit also not complete, and cannot be traced for 40m on S side. This has resulted in Hogg (1962) suggesting site unfinished.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Circuit also not complete, and cannot be traced for 40m on S side. This has resulted in Hogg (1962) suggesting site unfinished.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Traces of walling visible on rampart in places. Slight counterscarp. Circuit also not complete, and cannot be traced for 40m on S side. This has resulted in Hogg (1962) suggesting site unfinished.

Enclosing_Summary: As a result of topography, no defence is needed on S and only one bank on the W. Elsewhere, two widely-spaced banks with a ditch only on the outer. Interior 'divided' into series of stepped compartments, beginning with lowest NE point, then rising to W to highest outcrop point. Last internal area below the outcrop, is steep natural terrace, partly modified on N and E sides. W outcrop encircled by well-built low ramparts set on good foundations and possibly earliest phase of enclosure on site.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possible long and complex history to fort; possibly with smaller hillfort enclosing highest point on W first with subsequent enlargement on hillslopes below and to E.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: To N end small box-trench within NW ramparts, flanked by low spoil tip; a possible antiquarian excavation. No details.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Goginan Fach, Ceredigion (Goginan Fach; Castell Goginan-Fach;  Banc y Castell)
Enclosing_Summary: Bank up to 6m wide cuts off the spur NW-SE on NE, with scarped slopes elsewhere. A second bank diverges from the main rampart 30m W of the entrance. No ditch visible, possibly buried feature.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditch visible, possibly buried feature.

Enclosing_Summary: Slight defences remain, with low earth and stone bank to c. 4m wide and 0.5m to 1m high externally. Best on SE side. Possible additional bank on E side where most approachable. No ditch.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: External area c. 1.5ha. Internal area not defined.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone bank. Has been considered unfinished because of its irregular features, but low banks could have been surmounted by a possible palisade, but there is no evidence for this and the very exposed situation no doubt subject to severe erosion over time.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-y-Frwydd Llwyd Camp, Craig Ystradmeurig, Ceredigion (Pen y Ffrwyd Bannau Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by two ramparts, but not contiguous and possible phased construction suggested. Occupying a strong position on the hill, and incorporating rock outcrops on S side, the inner circuit is slighter,with no outer ditch and a few traces of stone walling on S side. In contrast outer circuit has bank to c. 10m by 2m high overall with strong outer rock-cut ditch, especially on N flanking the gateway, and on S side. Good traces of stone walling on its outer face. Hogg and Davies (1994, 268) suggest space between outer rampart and outwork as annexe between entrance trackway and the cliff edge.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Defined by two ramparts, but not contiguous and possible phased construction suggested, but not proven.

Enclosing_Summary: Single bank around most of circuit, apart from at the N end at the complex and strong oblique entrance, which has two additional banks up to 4m high and ditches. On aerial photographs E end of the middle bank is club-ended and there is an inturn to the inner bank on E.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Nadolig, Ceredigion (Christmas Castle; Castle Christmas)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by two widely-spaced ramparts, with an inner oval c. 122m NE-SW by 74m, and an outer, making the site 244m NE-SW by 183m overall. Internal area 3.28ha. Both circuits have banks and ditches, now reduced to scarps. Possible additional banks on E. Evidence of massive stone-work used in rampart walling.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of massive stone-work used in rampart walling.

Enclosing_Summary: Strong stony rampart to 3m high apart from on SW side above the Rheidol gorge 130m below. Traces of rock-cut ditch on E. Bank appears set out in straight sections with well-defined angles suggesting gang working. Original
Enclosing_Gang_Working_Comments: Strong rampart to 3m high appears set out in straight sections with well-defined angles suggesting gang working.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by fossilised set of field banks in farming landscape. Current field bank 4m wide and 1.5m external suggests an earlier defended enclosure. No external ditch.
Defined by two banks and ditch (silted up and forming a shelf) above steep natural slopes on all sides apart from N, where third scarp fronting an entrance.
Defined by slight earth bank c. 6m wide and to 1.8m high externally. No ditch visible.

Substantial curving bank and ditch with traces of counterscarp cut off the promontory at the more vulnerable S side, the bank rising to 4m - 5m above the ditch and 3m above the interior. It is possible that there is some evidence of scarping at N end of promontory.

Main_Display_Name: Mull, Cnoc na Sroine, Argyll & Bute (Caisteal na Srianga)
Enclosing_Summary: Inner and outer walled enclosures

Main enclosure (90m by 40m) on highest part of site where slight stony bank 2m-3m wide and to 0.3m high, more substantial on N. Rampart loops out enclosing second enclosure. A rampart also encloses entire site, best on SE. Steep W flanks of outcrop surmounted by low footing wall at top of the slope, possibly, originally, supporting timber defences. These slopes are further embellished with stone revetment. No evidence for ditches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Complex site, considered three phased by Davies and Hogg (1994).
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Steep W flanks of outcrop summounted by low footing wall at top of the slope, possibly, originally, supporting timber defences. These slopes are further embellished with stone revetment.

Main_Display_Name: Hen Gaer, Bow Street, Ceredigion (Pen Gaer, Bow Street; Broncastellan; Caer Shon)
Enclosing_Summary: Massive construction of carefully laid stone blocks of rampart walling, still exposed in places, to 3-4m high and 12m wide, with outer rock-cut ditch, best on NE
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Massive construction of carefully laid stone blocks of rampart walling, still exposed in places, to 3-4m high and 12m wide.

Main_Display_Name: y Gaer, Caron-Uwch-Clawdd, Ceredigion (y Gaer Hillfort, Lisbourne Road.)
Enclosing_Summary: Natural breaks of slope on N and S sides and very slight earthworks on SE, possibly part of a bank. Aerial photographs show possible curving length of bank on S side. In 1974, Ordnance Survey reported 100m length of curving scarp on N and change of slope on S of oval enclosure c. 90m long and perhaps 50m wide.

Inner circuit of bank and ditch to 3m high with slight counterscarp. Similar outer circuit lies slightly eccentric to inner, but has slighter defences. Widely-spaced ramparts between the two circuits, but converge with the counterscarp bank to E.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: It is possible that the site could be of two periods, but no details.

Main_Display_Name: Castell Tregaron, Ceredigion (Sunnyhill Wood Camp; Castell Sunnyhill)
Enclosing_Summary: Strong and curving double bank and ditch, with 6m interspace, on gentler NE cuts across the neck of the promontory. Steep faces to ramparts with outer circuit to 4.5m high and 20m wide at base with silted ditch. Probably fully walled, as tumbled stone and faces visible. Berm or terrace cut into rear side of rampart at N end suggests later modification. Possible that fort had phased construction. Inner rampart to 6m high on outer face has ditch to 3m deep. Outer face also has traces of stone walling.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Driver (2005) suggests that berm or terrace cut into rear side of rampart at N end indicates later modification and this, together with general morphology, points to possibility that fort had phased construction.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Stone-walled site, with traces of stone walling visible to both inner and outer ramparts.  Berm or terrace cut into rear side of outer rampart at N end. Possible timberwork.

Enclosing_Summary: Three massive banks cut off the promontory at the NE, the outer being less substantial, but has an outer rock-cut ditch, and rise to 7m high and 20m wide, incorporating natural outcrops. Evidence of stone revetments.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Evidence of stone revetments. Possibly stone-walled, at least in part.

Enclosing_Summary: No details.

Roughly circular in form defined by earthwork 'platform' or degraded bank rising to c. 1.5m and measuring c. 28m - 40m across at max. and c. 20m-25m across the top. Earthwork bank running down the slope from the platform possibly natural, but this is uncertain. No ditch nor entrance visible.

Two curving and widely-spaced ramparts and ditches, the inner c. 124m long. WWII excavations (no details) to parts of ramparts found inner enclosure had palisade running along summit of the promontories natural slopes.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Excavations to parts of ramparts and interior, found inner enclosure had palisade running along summit of the promontories natural slopes.

Enclosing_Summary: First phase N enclosure of 1.72 ha defended by a stone bank of packed rubble with timber revetment and outer ditch. Second phase of S enclosure of 2.28 defended by a bank revetted with stone with outer ditch and elaborate gate, later collapsed and site abandoned. Later r-occupied and defences remodelled in Phase 3. Finally defended area had additional ramparts constructed across the isthmus linking both summits, together with a new main gate as Phase 4 and site now extended to 4.4 ha in total.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Four phases determined by Daryll Forde in 1933-37 excavations.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: First phase N enclosure rampart of packed rubble with timber revetment and outer ditch. Second phase S enclosure of 2.28 defended by a bank revetted with stone with outer ditch. Later r-occupied and defences remodelled in Phase 3. Finally defended area had additional ramparts constructed across the isthmus linking both summits, together with a new main gate, as Phase 4.

Enclosing_Summary: Promontory cut off by two widely spaced glacis ramparts. Inner is c. 50m long and to 3m high and 8.5m wide. At S end rampart terminal turns in to form gate. C. 17m to E is 30m of outer rampart to 4.5m high and 13m wide. Outer ditch to 1.8m deep, with counterscarp.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch to 1.8m deep, with counterscarp.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by two widely separated banks without ditches to 2m high. Inner bank to 2m high has quarry ditch inside. Outer circuit, c. 20m distant on W and NW, reduced to c. 10m elsewhere. Along SE, where the two circuits produce a distinctive terrace, it is visible in erosion features as a slab-faced wall. Counterscarp on NW.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Outer circuit visible as slab-faced wall on SE. Counterscarp on NW.

Enclosing_Summary: Substantial curving earthen bank cuts off the promontory on the E, c. 2.5m high and 12m - 15m wide. Trace of a ditch of c. 0.5 - 1m deep and 4m wide.

Cropmark of a curvilinear single palisade trench 200m in diameter. Possible traces of a smaller circular enclosure approximately 100m in diameter have been observed within the enclosed area offset to the N.

Main_Display_Name: Cribyn Gaer, Ceredigion (Caer Maesmynach; Gaer Maesmynach)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank and ditch to 5m high and 15m wide and replaced by a scarp slope on SW. Additional outer works on the SE, where entrance to 3m high and 14m wide.

Generally single bank and ditch with two banks and ditches on E side, the outer detached, with counterscarp to inner bank ditch. Site part-eroded by cultivation and destruction by ploughing, but main bank in good condition on N and E, and ditch has disappeared apart from traces on W and a silted E stretch to 6m wide.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly phased: original roughly oval enclosure c. 70m-80m across was extended to S, as traces of possible eroded cross-bank bisects the fort from E-W.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Generally single bank and ditch with two banks and ditches on E side, the outer detached, with counterscarp to inner bank ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditches lost for most part, but traces survive on W and E.

Main_Display_Name: Coed-Parc Gaer, Ceredigion (Betws-Bledrws; Gaer Coed Parc)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by three ramparts, all three together only being visible on W side. On E, inner rampart most obvious and best preserved, to 2m high and 7m wide, with an external ditch.   Second bank, closely-spaced to inner but slighter, clearly visible, on W side. Rock outcrops.  Probable third line, more widely-spaced, further out to NW.
Natural protected by steep slopes on S above the river. Two substantial banks and rock-cut ditches (to 1.9m deep), using impressive natural rock outcrop on E side, less high elsewhere.

Main_Display_Name: Crugllwyn Camp, Ceredigion (Crugllwyn-Llwyd; Crug Llwyn Llwyd; Crug Llwyn-Llwyd)
Enclosing_Summary: Formerly single bank and ditch to 4m high and 130m long cuts off the promontory on NE. No further details.

Main_Display_Name: Gaer Pwntan, Ceredigion (Caer Pwntan; Castell Pwntan; Pen-y-Gaer, Penbryn)
Enclosing_Summary: Because of destruction interpretation of site difficult. Apparently stone-walled with two widely-spaced ramparts, best on N and S sides. On N side slight length of circuit survives in improved pasture, On S low earthworks to 140m long and to 0.8m high in improved pasture possibly mark the lines of banks and ditches. Defences on E and W destroyed, but ditch of outer rampart survives beneath ground on E and possibly same elsewhere.

Circular inner enclosure c. 40m diameter. Outer is fragmentary c. 150m across. Cropmark of an outer ditch only shows on S and W sides. It is concentric to the inner enclosure, c. 30m - 40m distant from it.
Single wall cutting off a promontory
Defined by stony bank, c. 1m high and 5.5m wide. Large internal quarry ditch. Outer ditch not visible.

Bank, c. 2.5m high, extends c. 20m - 25m either side of a simple 2m wide gap entrance cuts off the narrow neck of the promontory on E with bank to 2.5m high and 15m wide.  Natural ravines running up to the neck artificially deepened and widened to create ditch c. 5m wide in front of the bank adjacent to the entrance. Counterscarp bank to 1m high on the outer lip of the ditch.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Possible earth and stone bank. Counterscarp bank to 1m high on the outer lip of the ditch.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Natural ravines running up to the neck artificially deepened and widened to create ditch c. 5m wide in front of the bank adjacent to the entrance.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Llifry, Ceredigion (Pen-y-Gaer, Bank Green Grove; Caer-Lifry)
Enclosing_Summary: Sides ploughed down on N and S and now sharp breaks of slope above the steep slopes. Better preserved at each end. W best and defended by a bank of spread stone (shattered shale), 6m wide and to 0.5m high, with slight traces of external ditch. E end almost destroyed and now a wide shattered shale spread. However, ditch, however, better preserved to 6m wide and to 0.5m deep.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Traces of ditch to W, better on E.

Enclosing_Summary: Inner circuit c. 50m-60m diameter with bank to 1.5m high where highest close to a NW-facing entrance, else c. 1m high. Ditch shows in places as slight hollow, except on SE-SW sides. Outer circuit lies some 12m - 15m from inner, with bank on N side to 1m high, terminating at NW entrance, but fading to NE, where line of outer ditch visible to 0.7m deep. Old track on SE, S and W may be line of outer circuit. Possible third line of banks on N side.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Possible third line of banks on N side not included.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Inner ditch shows in places as slight hollow, except on SE-SW sides. Outer ditch visible on NE.

Enclosing_Summary: Little trace of site, but evidence of steep break of slope on SE to 1.5m high, now covered with hedge, possibly part of a circular circuit c. 110m diameter.  On NW side defined by concentric ditches, now cropmarks, c. 10m apart.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: On NW side defined by concentric ditches, now cropmarks, c. 10m apart. Number not defined.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank c. 2m -15m wide and to 0.5m high maximum. Best preserved on N side. No ditch visible.
A single rampart round most of the circuit, with an additional rampart and ditch on the line of easiest approach.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Across the easiest line of approach

Enclosing_Summary: Defined initially by c. 120m of curving cropmark ditch on N side of enclosure. On site this proved to be a low bank, to 0.8m high, and ditch, whilst to S bank continues as a low, levelled earthwork.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Rough estimate of internal area only.

Enclosing_Summary: N/A as not a hillfort
Oval in plan it comprises two concentric ditches separated by 10-13m.

On SE and NW, no trace of bank, but probably buried feature. On NE bank to 2m high externally, but level with interior. No ditch visible. At SW end is a bank, up to 2m high externally, with ditch. Simple gap entrance on NE. Additional bank runs NE from NE tip of fort.

Main_Display_Name: Welwyn, Hertfordshire (Welwyn Garden City; Welch's Farm; Datchworth)
Enclosing_Summary: N/A as not a hillfort
Defined by bank, with no ditch visible, and bank incorporated into field boundaries on N side where to 2m high; elsewhere just a scarp.
N/A as not a hillfort

Defined by earthen inner bank and ditch, best on W where to 1.5m high and to 20m wide. Ditch no longer visible and probably buried feature on other sides and bank on N now scarp to c. 3m high. At E end traces of outer bank, but much cultivated and spread to c. 30m. This has been destroyed on N by plough and on S by road. Not visible on W now. No outer ditch visible.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Inner bank only in each quadrant, and scarp feature on N side. Probably two circuits with ditches in prehistory.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Inner earthen bank with no revetment seen.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Inner rampart outer ditch on W, no longer visible and probably buried feature on other sides. No ditch where traces of outer circuit and also  possibly buried feature now.

Enclosing_Summary: Possibly originally bivallate, but now reduced to weak bank and ditch in places or scarp. On N bank to 2.5m exterior height with steep outer slope and berm c. 9m wide and ditch, at E end of which reduced to scarp. On S and W scarp to 2m high with deep ditch on W and possible counterscarp on S.

Main_Display_Name: Gaer Fawr Lower Camp, Mynydd y Gaer, Neath Port Talbot (Mynydd y Gaer (Gaer Fawr) Lower Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Inner enclosure, c. 55m by 30m of c. 0.1ha internal area and defined by two banks and ditches with counterscarp, with total width of c.25m. Damaged and part lost to N, its circuits were probably in place originally before cultivation intervened. Outside this central enclosure,for a distance the ground rises gently to a slight intermediate bank, visible on the S and E, but much damaged on W. A slight outer bank survives on S and E but not other sides. Two slight additional lengths of bank on the SE side run parallel to the intermediate and outer banks to give six banks in total (including inner enclosure) for a short distance here. Also on S, short length of bank curves from intermediate bank towards inner enclosure. The function of these extra banks is obscure. On W side, the intermediate and outer banks seem to coalesc, but there is damage here with modern wall and field bank.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possibly phased or multiple enclosure. Inner enclosure 0.1ha, outer enclosure area c. 3.4ha.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Complex and quadrants estimated. Outer ramparts lost to N.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Two ditches defined, probably more as buried features.

Main_Display_Name: Fort At Craig Ty Isaf, Neath Port Talbot (Craig Ty Isaf Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by ruinous rubble wall following the complete circuit to form enclosure measuring c. 65m E-W by 40m N-S and enclosing 0.2ha. Hardly visible on S side but, on N, where follows spine of ridge, shows as spread of stones and rubble up to 9m wide and 2.5m on inner face. To E end of enclosure two additional outer banks and ditches, the first, or middle, bank separated from inner circuit described above by some 6-20m with shallow ditch for some 10m to N. Middle bank slightly curved with ditch, c. 10m overall and to 2m high. Outermost rampart straight with ditch, c. 12 wide and to 2m high overall with short length of counterscarp at end.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Outermost rampart straight with ditch, c. 12m wide and to 2m high overall with short length of counterscarp at end. This outer rampart is unbroken and, without an entrance gap, cuts off access into the interior as suggested by RCAHMW (1976, 48), similar to the later additions at Dinas Powys dated to 12th century AD; thus it is possibly a later addition to an original site comprising the two inner ramparts and E entrance.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Inner bank shows complete circuit of ruinous walls.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Rubble walls. Short length of counterscarp to outer rampart.

Main_Display_Name: Pen y Castell, Cwmafan, Neath Port Talbot
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by bank which follows the contours, only 0.3m internally but to nearly 3m external. Simple entrance at E end. Outside bank is berm c. 6m-10m wide followed by a second rampart which has gone on NE and at E of N side. Along W half of N side it shows as bank 3m wide and to 0.6m high and is best on W where to 6m wide and nearly 1m high. Along S forms a scarp fading into the natural slope. No ditches visible. Possibly buried features.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Outer bank has gone on NE and at E of N side.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Traces of stone about the banks suggesting earth and rubble construction,
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: No ditches visible. Possibly buried features.

Main_Display_Name: Buarth y Gaer, Neath Port Talbot (Mynydd-y-Gaer)
Enclosing_Summary: Simple in plan measuring 135m E-W by 107m with internal area of 1.1ha. Single bank and ditch to 10m overall, best on E and NE where bank to 2m externally from bottom of ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Cefn yr Argoed, Neath Port Talbot
Enclosing_Summary: Substantial bank with U-shaped ditch, former to 1.5m external height, latter to c. 6m width at top.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch absent on SW and slighter on NW.

Enclosing_Summary: Appear to have been two ramparts and ditches, enclosing an egg-shaped interior of c. 85m NE-SW by 60m of c. 0.4ha. Outer ditch gone around nearly all the circuit. An outer bank along most of the S side, and an inner bank around the N. Where best preserved, each bank stands c. 2.5m high above bottom of the ditch, and just S of a SW entrance defences measure c. 27m wide overall.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch gone around nearly all the circuit.

Enclosing_Summary: Defined by two widely-spaced ramparts, possibly a multiple enclosure site, enclosing 0.57ha and 4.5ha. Large sub-circular outer enclosure, 240m NW-SE by 254m, of bank with ditch and counterscarp, all gone on NW quadrant. Bank exists to E of farm buildings and ditch and and bank progressively fainter as go N, to reappear again where meet wooded slopes on NE. Within woodland on NE the defences better preserved. Small stones on outer banks and ditches in wooded section suggest rubble and earthen construction. Trig point on W  end of outer bank, which stops to NW of wood and to W. An inner circuit provides a sub-rectangular enclosure measuring c. 82m NW-SE by 48-68m of bank and ditches, wooded to NE, where also better preserved and here the bank and ditch reach  0.5m high (internal) and 2m deep (on outside) respectively.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Defences lost on NW and SW.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Large sub-circular outer enclosure, 240m NW-SE by 254m, of bank with ditch and counterscarp, all gone on NW quadrant.

Main_Display_Name: Half Moon Camp, Margam, Neath Port Talbot
Enclosing_Summary: Single rampart best preserved on NE, where c. 9m wide and 1m from outside, but only a scarp on S. Detached length of bank on W is out of line with rest of the earthwork but probably belongs to it; similar to rampart but only 7m wide. Outer ditch only on NE where 5m wide and 0.3m deep.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer ditch only on NE where 5m wide and 0.3m deep.

Enclosing_Summary: Single dry-stone bank to 1.5m with ditch on S and SW, with steep natural slopes elsewhere.

Main_Display_Name: Mynydd-y-Castell Camp, Margam, Neath Port Talbot
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by single massive bank or scarp, ditch and counterscarp. Bank best on E side, where to 15m wide and 8.5m external height. O N and W forms a scarp of similar height and to 12m wide. Ditch to 4.5m wide and counterscarp visible on E, SW and NW sides, elsewhere is a terrace some 5m-6m wide. Bare crags incorporated in circuit at S end.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Blaen-y-Cwm, Margam, Neath Port Talbot (Caer Blaen y Cwm)
Enclosing_Summary: The fort is defined by double banks, c. 4-6m wide, with medial ditch and c. 1.5m high above the ditch bottom. The overall width is 11-15m.

Main_Display_Name: Piercefield Great Camp, Monmouth (Pierce Wood Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Impressive three banks with medial ditches of main defence on SW side, where the ground slopes away less steeply. On the long SE side reduced bank or wall of low band of tumbled stone c. 5-6m wide. Berm.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Banks composed of large angular stone or earth. Berm in evidence.

Enclosing_Summary: A single rampart 3.0m in height internally and 3.6m externally, built from chalk rubble, and a wide outer defensive ditch only visible in the N and E quadrants. The banks are made of chalk rubble.

A complex sequence with extensive medieval re-modelling of the two Iron Age ramparts and ditches. The original outer ditch appears to have been about 13m wide at the top, 4m deep with a flat bottom, the inner ditch smaller and round-bottomed, the two ramparts consisted of layers of chalk rubble and loam.

Main_Display_Name: Bloodgate Hill, Norfolk (Burgh Dykes; Burrow Dykes)
Enclosing_Summary: A single bank and ditch, bank now survives as a slight rise of earth and flint rubble, the ditch to a maximum of 1.4m depth and 22m wide on the E. Excavation (Penn 2006) shows ditch to be re-cut after primary silting,

On the W no rampart but a steep natural scarp approximately 3m high above the level of the marsh, and on the N, E and S by an earthen bank and outer ditch. On the W and S sides, where the natural slope of the ground is more gentle, there is also an outer counterscarp bank. The inner bank stands between 1m and 2m in height and the counterscarp bank between 0.4m and 1.4m. The ditch, which has become partly infilled but remains open to a depth of up to 1m, is between 10m and 17m in width.

Main_Display_Name: Piercefield Little Camp, Monmouth (Pierce Wood Camp)
Enclosing_Summary: Precipitous Piercefield Cliffs form N defence with bank to 3m high on remainder. Ditch, averaging 0.8m deep, visible at SW corner and S end of W side.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Precipitous Piercefield Cliffs form N defence.
Enclosing_Gang_Working_Comments: N side protected by Piercefield Cliffs to River Wye.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Ditch, averaging 0.8m deep, visible at SW corner and S end of W side.

Enclosing_Summary: A single bank and ditch, now ploughed flat. Excavation has shown the ditch to be two phased, V-shaped in section and between 1.7m and 2m deep measured from the present surface of the ploughsoil. On the W and N sides of the enclosure and around the NE corner it is approximately 2m wide, and on the S side and the E side S of the entrance it is approximately 5.8m wide.

Banks survive to 3m high in places and the ditches 3m deep. Excavations in 1914 (Gray 1933) and 1959 (Gregory 1986) have shown the outer ditch to be 2m deeper and the inner rampart to have been built of chalk with two slots in the top interpreted as the base of a wooden platform with a possible palisade at the front, there was also a rear revetment.

Excavations across the bank and ditch in 1948 showed a bank of loam c.12.5 m wide, perhaps with a rear revetment, surviving to a height of 1m and an external ditch 3m deep, 11m wide with a flat bottom. Counter-scarp bank in places. Dating was inconclusive.

Main_Display_Name: Warren Hill, Briton Ferry, Neath Port Talbot
Enclosing_Summary: Defined by strong bank and ditch, now reduced to scarp with terrace below. Possible counterscarp. Bank preserved on S and E sides where c. 15m wide overall and 5m high. Whole of N quadrant destroyed by road construction an reservoir in interior. Entrance position uncertain. Cutting of water main in 1971 provided profile through E and W banks. Showed rampart 6m wide above rock-cut slope leading to ditch 1m deep. Another ditch encircled area of hillfort c. 20m inside rampart terrace, up to 6m wide and 1.5m deep, but its bank gone.

Now forms rectangular enclosure c.70m wide NE-SW with extension c. 25m wide for further 45m to SE; both cut by quarry on SW. Main enclosure limestone rubble bank. Along SE side width of bank decreases and separated in front by berm from a scarp, beyond which traces of ditch, but only visible for c.10m. Outer height of rampart c. 5m .Bank forming the extension very slight, especially on NE. Banks of the main enclosure and of the extension both turn slightly northwards, suggesting that little destroyed along this side.

Outer bank c. 1.0m external to 1.5m internal height with c.16.0m wide. Middle outer bank 2.0m high internal height with ditch c. 14.0m wide. Middle inner bank to 1.10m internal with ditch 13.0m wide. Inner bank 1.8m and 2.0m external and 0.2m and 0.4m internal height. Possible revetment inside inner bank. Earth and stone construction likely.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts and ditches lost through development in S sector.
Enclosing_Surface_Comments: Earth and stone baks likely. Revetted in parts.

Enclosing_Summary: Inner bank and ditch visible to c.1m-1.5m outside and 0.4m-0.6m inside. Outer bank mostly only c. 0.4m, but nearly lost on S where quarrying and animal damage. Here possible annexe. . Undulations and stone piles in interior possibly result of field clearance.

W half of N side natural slope for defence;  towards E end bank and ditch begin abruptly, c.2.5-3m external height, 0.8m internal  and ditch depth of 1.2m. This bank continues E side above steep slopes, ditch ending abruptly at SE corner. Large stones lie in ditch at N end. On S bank continues, with lower internal height to c. 0.5m, outside of which berm, 5m wide, becoming shallow ditch in places, with bank to 0.5m high. Steep scarp 2.5m high below this, after which ground levels out. On W side two scarps, upper to 2m high, lower to 0.7m high with wide berm between, after which land drops steeply. Outer scarp here becomes low bank towards S, with further steep scarp below, and at bottom farm track. In middle of this side short stretch of the outer ditch and bank, former 3m wide and 1.2m deep, the latter 1.2m high on both sides.

Main_Display_Name: Llanmelin Wood Camp and Llanmelin Outpost, Caerwent, Monmouth
Enclosing_Summary: Main, roughly elliptical enclosure, has two and three ramparts, highest on the SE near the entrance.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Main enclosure 1.32ha internal area, 'Outpost' 0.14ha internal area.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Complex of annexes on SE of main enclosure confuse quadrants analysis.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Banks mainly up-cast, although on NE side innermost bank wholly of rubble and faced with roughly-coursed masonry both internally and externally.

Enclosing_Summary: Two artificial defensive lines cut off neck of ridge on crests of very steep slopes which form N edge of narrow, high hanging valley. The first and inner line defends an area c. 542m long with maximum width of 77m, and c. 2.52ha internal area. This tree-covered bank of limestone rubble runs W-E along crest of a steep natural scarp before curving across neck of the ridge to stop just short of its N edge. Old field-wall follows the top of the bank. No ditch, but possible attempt to construct one. Possible quarry ditch visible. Outer line similar in construction to inner, but poorer condition, varying in height from 0.5 to 3m. Modern, vertical-sided mining cut in possible position of original ditch.

On S and W three ramparts with two, much eroded, on E. Possible phased construction. Large, tree covered, bank, 4-5m high exterior and 1.6m high interior at N end of site curves to W side becoming a 4m high scarp. At N end of the fort a long, low, truncated, flat-topped mound c. 1-1.5m high. Massive bank, ditch and counterscarp at S, where inner bank 2.2-2.5m high interior and 4-5m high exterior, with flat bottomed ditch 4m wide and a bank of 1.6m high. Bank higher towards E, where 3m high, but outer decreases to zero where a private garden encroaches.
Enclosing_Multiperiod_Comments: Possible phased construction, but no details.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: One defined but probably three in total.

Enclosing_Summary: Enclosed by massive bank on NE and NW, with two or three smaller banks outside on NW side, as shown on Spencer and Nash-Williams plan of 1936. These outer banks now not visible on NE, but excavation proved once existed, with V-shaped ditches between. Main bank built in four stages and inner face had two steeply sloping rough walled revetments.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Probable that once three banks completed circuit. possible fourth bank on W.
Enclosing_Excavation_Comments: Outer banks not visible on NE, but excavation proved existed with V-shaped ditches between. Excavations by S.H. Sell 1998-99 found construction of central rampart of W defences incorporated at least one revetment on inner face; outer face seaward mostly lost to erosion. One of trenches outside W defences showed possible flattened fourth bank.
Enclosing_Ditches_Comments: Outer banks not visible on NE, but excavation proved existed with V-shaped ditches between.

Enclosing_Summary: W rampart begins at W edge of ravine to S, and separated from it by bank of c. 4m high. W ramparts then continue N with ditch separating inner and outer bank, the former c. 2.25m high, the latter c.1.5-2m high. Ditch c. 2m wide. Entire rampart c. 30m across. N ramparts measure similar in height but width c. 25m, partly due to encroachment of  electricity sub-station sited immediately N of ramparts.
Enclosing_Circuit_Comments: Ramparts run NE to SW in an arc.

Enclosing_Summary: Sub-oval in form enclosed by a single stony bank 2-3m wide and up to 1.2m high which survives in woodland, and as the trace of an arc in pasture to the S. Possibly once bivallate. No evidence of a ditch.

Inner rampart possibly Iron Age but earthworks of chapel make interpretation difficult. and chapel and circular enclosure in interior. Second and sub-rectangular circuit surrounds first at a distance of 30-60m, its nature unknown and much affected by the Skirrid quarry in NW side. Third circuit surrounds first and second and ultimately joins the S side of the latter. It is possible a fourth circuit lies within first and second but uncertain.
